
const SITUATION_SETS = [
  {id:"sr1",title:"Bases Loaded Jam",emoji:"🔥",color:"#ef4444",diff:2,
    situation:{inning:"Bot 6",outs:1,count:"1-2",runners:[1,2,3],score:[3,4]},
    desc:"Bases loaded, one out, down by one in the 6th. Every position has a job. Can you see the whole field?",
    debrief:"The pitcher threw a low fastball, and the catcher had already set up low-and-away — they were on the same page. The batter hit a grounder to short, who flipped to second for one, and the relay to first completed the double play. Meanwhile, the smart baserunner on third read the sharp grounder and held — if he'd run blindly, he would have been the third out. The pitcher's location, the catcher's setup, and the baserunner's patience all worked together.",
    teamworkTakeaway:"A double play only works when the pitcher pitches for grounders, the catcher calls for the right location, and the baserunner reads the ball before committing. One breakdown in the chain changes everything.",
    questions:[
      {pos:"pitcher",id:"sr1a",conceptTag:"pitch-sequencing",title:"Pitcher: Navigate the Jam",diff:2,cat:"pitcher",ageMin:9,ageMax:99,
        options:["Throw a fastball low for a ground-ball double play","Go for the strikeout with a high fastball","Pitch around this batter — walk in the tying run to face an easier hitter","Throw a changeup middle-middle to get ahead"],
        best:0,explanations:["With bases loaded and one out, a ground ball double play ends the inning. Keeping the ball low gives you the best chance at a grounder. Even a single ground ball gets a force at home. You're playing the percentages. The numbers back this up: with bases loaded and one out, the expected run value is 1.59. After a double play (bases empty, two outs), it drops to just 0.11. That's a massive 1.48-run swing on one play!","Going for a strikeout sounds great, but high fastballs with bases loaded are dangerous, because if the batter makes contact, it's likely a sac fly (run scores) or a line drive. Ground balls are your best friend here.","Walking in the tying run on purpose is almost never the right play — you'd hand them a free run and still have bases loaded. That only makes sense if the next hitter is dramatically weaker and you're OK giving up the lead.","A changeup middle-middle is a gift to a hitter in this situation, which means keep the ball low and on the corners. You want weak contact, not center-cut pitches that get driven."],
        rates:[88,25,5,10],concept:"With bases loaded and one out, pitch for the ground-ball double play. Low pitches create grounders.",anim:"doubleplay",
        explSimple:["A ground ball can turn into a double play and end the inning! Keep the ball low.","High pitches might get hit hard with bases loaded. Ground balls are safer.","Walking in a run on purpose is almost always a bad idea.","Don't throw it right down the middle — that's too easy to hit hard."]},
      {pos:"catcher",id:"sr1b",conceptTag:"dp-positioning",title:"Catcher: Set Up the DP",diff:2,cat:"catcher",ageMin:9,ageMax:99,
        options:["Set up low and outside — induce a ground ball to the right side for a 1-2-3 double play","Set up high and tight — get a popup or strikeout","Set up middle-middle — let the pitcher throw his best pitch wherever","Call for a pitchout — the runner at third might be stealing home"],
        best:0,explanations:["Perfect setup! Low-and-away pitches produce ground balls, and with the infield set for a double play, a grounder to the right side gives you the 1-2-3 (catcher to first to home or similar) or 6-4-3 path. You're thinking one step ahead. At a 1-2 count, the batting average drops to just .180 — the pitcher has a big edge. Setting up low-and-away maximizes that advantage.","High and tight might get a strikeout, but it also risks a hit batter (loading is already done) or a fly ball that scores the runner from third on a sac fly. Ground balls are the priority.","Never set up middle-middle in a pressure situation. Give the pitcher a target. Your job as catcher is to frame the strategy — location matters more than ever with bases loaded.","A pitchout with bases loaded makes no sense. Runners aren't going anywhere because every base is occupied. A pitchout is just ball one for no reason."],
        rates:[88,30,10,5],concept:"The catcher sets the strategy. With bases loaded and one out, target low-and-away to get the ground-ball double play.",anim:"doubleplay",
        explSimple:["Setting up low gets ground balls, and a ground ball can be a double play! Smart thinking.","High pitches might become fly balls that score a run. Low is safer here.","Always give your pitcher a target. Middle-middle is lazy catching.","A pitchout with bases loaded makes no sense — nobody is stealing!"]},
      {pos:"baserunner",id:"sr1c",conceptTag:"baserunning-rates",title:"Runner on Third: Read the Play",diff:2,cat:"baserunner",ageMin:9,ageMax:99,
        options:["On a ground ball, sprint home immediately no matter what","On a ground ball, read it first — go home on a ball hit to the right side or slowly, hold if it's a sharp grounder near home","Tag up on any fly ball and sprint home","Stay close to third and only score on a base hit"],
        best:1,explanations:["Sprinting home on every ground ball is reckless. A sharp grounder right at the pitcher or catcher means you'll be thrown out at home easily. You need to read the ball — direction and speed — before committing.","This is smart baserunning! On a ball hit to the right side (first or second baseman), you have time because the throw home is longer. On a slow roller, you can score too. But a sharp grounder near the pitcher or third baseman? Hold — you'll be a dead duck at home. Smart baserunners score from third on about 88% of tag-up opportunities, but only when they read the play correctly.","Tagging on every fly ball is too aggressive. A fly to shallow left or center means the throw home will beat you. Only tag on deep flies where the outfielder needs a long throw. Read the depth before deciding.","Waiting for a base hit is too passive. With one out and bases loaded, there are many ways to score — ground ball force at another base, sac fly, wild pitch. You need to be ready to go on the right play, not just sit there."],
        rates:[15,88,20,12],concept:"Good baserunning means reading the ball off the bat. On a ground ball from third, go on balls hit away from home; hold on sharp grounders near the battery.",anim:"score",
        explSimple:["Don't just run on every ground ball — some are hit right at the catcher or pitcher!","Smart! Read where the ball goes first. If it's hit to the right side, you have time to score.","Only tag up on deep fly balls. Shallow ones mean the throw will beat you home.","Don't just stand there! With bases loaded, there are lots of chances to score."]}
    ]},
  {id:"sr2",title:"Steal Attempt at Second",emoji:"💨",color:"#06b6d4",diff:2,
    situation:{inning:"Top 4",outs:0,count:"1-1",runners:[1],score:[2,2]},
    desc:"A speedster takes off for second base! The pitcher, catcher, and shortstop all have a role. Who executes?",
    debrief:"The pitcher used a slide step, cutting delivery time from 1.5 seconds to 1.2 seconds. That extra 0.3 seconds gave the catcher time to make a clean transfer and fire to second. The shortstop timed his break perfectly — arriving at the bag with the throw, straddling the front edge, and sweeping a low tag. The runner was out by half a step. Every fraction of a second mattered.",
    teamworkTakeaway:"Stopping a stolen base is a relay chain: pitcher's delivery time + catcher's transfer and throw + fielder's tag. If any link is slow, the runner is safe. The slide step is what makes the whole chain possible.",
    questions:[
      {pos:"pitcher",id:"sr2a",conceptTag:"steal-window",title:"Pitcher: Quick to the Plate",diff:2,cat:"pitcher",ageMin:9,ageMax:99,
        options:["Use a slide step to get the ball to your catcher quickly","Use your full windup for maximum velocity — blow the batter away","Step off the rubber and try to catch the runner leaning","Hold the ball for 5+ seconds to freeze the runner"],
        best:0,explanations:["The slide step is the pitcher's best weapon against stolen bases. It cuts your delivery time from ~1.5 seconds to ~1.2 seconds, giving the catcher a much better chance to throw the runner out. You still throw a competitive pitch. Here's the math: a normal delivery takes about 1.5 seconds. A slide step cuts it to about 1.2-1.3 seconds. With an average catcher pop time of 2.0 seconds, that 0.3-second difference is the difference between safe and out.","A full windup with a runner on first is a gift to the base stealer, because the long delivery gives the runner an enormous jump. Always use the stretch position with runners on base.","Stepping off is a fine move occasionally, but the runner has already taken off, since once the steal is on, your job is to deliver the ball quickly. Stepping off wastes time and accomplishes nothing.","Holding the ball too long will get you a balk call! You must deliver within a reasonable time, because besides, the runner's jump starts with your first move — holding the ball just delays the inevitable."],
        rates:[88,8,25,10],concept:"The slide step cuts delivery time to help your catcher throw out a base stealer. Quick to the plate is a pitcher's job.",anim:"steal",
        explSimple:["A slide step gets the ball to your catcher faster so they can throw the runner out!","A full windup is too slow with a runner on base. They'll steal easily.","Stepping off doesn't help once the runner is already going. Just throw fast.","Holding the ball too long can be a balk! Just deliver it quickly."]},
      {pos:"catcher",id:"sr2b",conceptTag:"steal-window",title:"Catcher: The Throw Down",diff:2,cat:"catcher",ageMin:9,ageMax:99,
        options:["Catch, quick transfer to bare hand, throw to the shortstop side of second base","Catch, stand up fully, take a crow hop, then throw to second","Catch and throw to second base on the first-base side","Pump fake to freeze the runner, then throw"],
        best:0,explanations:["Textbook! The quick transfer (glove to bare hand) is the most important skill for throwing out runners. Throw to the shortstop side of the bag because the shortstop is covering on a steal with a right-handed batter. Every millisecond counts — catch, transfer, throw. Elite catchers have a pop time (catch to throw arriving at 2B) of 1.85 seconds. Average is 2.0 seconds. Every tenth of a second matters when the runner's total time is around 3.3-3.5 seconds.","Standing up and crow-hopping takes too long. The runner gains another step or two during your setup. Elite catchers throw from their crouch or a slight rise — never a full stand-up-and-hop.","Throwing to the first-base side of second is wrong on a steal because the shortstop (or second baseman) needs the ball on the side where they can apply the tag. Usually the shortstop covers, so throw to the shortstop side (left side of the bag from the catcher's view).","A pump fake on a straight steal just wastes time. Pump fakes are for rundowns or deception plays, not when a runner is in a full sprint to second. Every fraction of a second matters."],
        rates:[88,12,20,10],concept:"On a steal, quick transfer and accurate throw to the tag side of the bag. Don't waste time standing up or pump-faking.",anim:"steal",
        explSimple:["Catch it, get it out of your glove fast, and throw to where the fielder is waiting!","Standing up takes too long! The runner will be safe by the time you throw.","Throw to the side where the fielder is catching it and making the tag.","A pump fake just wastes time when the runner is sprinting. Throw it!"]},
      {pos:"shortstop",id:"sr2c",conceptTag:"steal-window",title:"Shortstop: Cover the Bag",diff:2,cat:"fielder",ageMin:9,ageMax:99,
        options:["Break toward second as the pitcher delivers, straddle the bag, give a low tag","Sprint to second before the pitch — get there early","Stay in your normal position until you see the throw, then run to the bag","Cheat toward second by standing right next to the bag before the pitch"],
        best:0,explanations:["Perfect timing! Break toward second as the pitcher starts his delivery. Straddle the front of the bag so you can catch the throw and sweep a tag down in one motion. Arriving with the ball (or just before) gives you the best tag position. With zero outs, the steal break-even rate is 72% — the runner needs to be safe 72% of the time for stealing to be worth the risk. Good defense pushes that success rate down.","Getting to the bag too early leaves a massive hole in the infield. If the batter hits the ball where you were standing, it's a free base hit. Time your break so you arrive with the throw, not minutes before it.","Waiting until you see the throw is way too late. You need to read the steal attempt and break toward second as the pitch is delivered. If you wait for the throw, you'll be late to the bag and the runner slides in safe.","Standing next to the bag before the pitch tells the batter and runners exactly what's happening. It also creates a huge gap in the infield defense. Your break should be timed with the pitch, not pre-positioned."],
        rates:[88,20,10,15],concept:"On a steal, the shortstop times the break to arrive at second with the throw. Straddle the bag and give a low sweep tag.",anim:"steal",
        explSimple:["Time it right! Run to the bag as the pitcher throws, catch the ball, and tag low.","Getting there too early leaves a big hole where you're supposed to be fielding.","If you wait until you see the throw, you'll be too late. Start moving when the pitch is thrown.","Standing right at the bag before the pitch gives away the play and leaves a gap."]}
    ]},
  {id:"sr3",title:"Sacrifice Bunt Situation",emoji:"🎯",color:"#22c55e",diff:2,
    situation:{inning:"Bot 7",outs:0,count:"0-0",runners:[1],score:[3,3]},
    desc:"Tie game, late innings, runner on first, nobody out. The bunt is on! Every defender and the batter must execute.",
    debrief:"The pitcher threw a high fastball — the toughest pitch to bunt. The third baseman charged hard and the first baseman crashed in from the other side, creating a wall of defenders. The batter did the smart thing and bunted softly down the first-base line, away from the charging third baseman. The pitcher fielded it, threw to first (where the second baseman was covering), and the runner moved to second. Sacrifice successful, but the defense made it as hard as possible.",
    teamworkTakeaway:"Bunt defense is choreography — every defender has an assigned role. The pitcher makes the bunt difficult, corners charge, middle infielders cover the vacated bases. The batter's job is to find the gap in the defense. Both sides are executing a plan.",
    questions:[
      {pos:"pitcher",id:"sr3a",conceptTag:"bunt-defense",title:"Pitcher: Defend the Bunt",diff:2,cat:"pitcher",ageMin:9,ageMax:99,
        options:["Throw a high fastball — bunts on high pitches pop up","Throw your best breaking ball low to make the bunt difficult","Throw a fastball right down the middle for an easy bunt","Throw inside to jam the batter and make the bunt roll foul"],
        best:0,explanations:["High fastballs are the hardest pitch to bunt successfully. Bunts on high pitches tend to pop up (free out) or go foul. You're making the batter's job as hard as possible while keeping the ball in a zone that's tough to get down. Studies show that bunts on high fastballs result in popups or foul balls significantly more often than bunts on low pitches. You're turning the batter's sacrifice into your advantage.","Breaking balls low are easier to bunt because the batter can angle the bat down naturally. You're actually helping the bunter by throwing where the bat naturally goes during a bunt.","A fastball down the middle is the easiest pitch to bunt — you're handing the batter a perfect bunt opportunity. Never make it easy for the offense when they're trying to sacrifice.","Inside pitches can work, but they're risky — if the batter squares and gets hit, it's a free base and now you have runners on first and second with nobody out, which means high fastballs are safer and more effective."],
        rates:[85,15,5,30],concept:"High fastballs are the best anti-bunt pitch. They're hard to get down and tend to pop up.",anim:"bunt",
        explSimple:["High pitches are really hard to bunt! They usually pop up or go foul.","Low pitches are actually easier to bunt. Don't help the bunter!","Don't throw it right down the middle — that's the easiest pitch to bunt.","Inside pitches might hit the batter and put another runner on base."]},
      {pos:"thirdBase",id:"sr3b",conceptTag:"bunt-defense",title:"Third Base: Crash or Hold?",diff:2,cat:"fielder",ageMin:9,ageMax:99,
        options:["Charge hard toward home plate as the pitcher delivers — field the bunt early","Stay back at third and wait for the ball to come to you","Charge halfway, then read whether the bunt is toward you or the pitcher","Stay back to protect against a fake bunt and slash hit"],
        best:0,explanations:["Crashing hard is the aggressive play and the right one! If you can field the bunt early, you might have a throw to second base to get the lead runner — that's the ideal outcome. At minimum, you field the bunt quickly for the out at first.","Staying back means the bunt dies between you, the pitcher, and the catcher. The runner moves to second easily and now it's second and nobody out. You have to be aggressive on a bunt.","Charging halfway is hesitation, and hesitation kills you on bunts. By the time you read it, the runner is already at second. You need to commit to the charge and trust the pitcher to cover anything hit back toward the mound.","Protecting against a slash hit is overthinking it. The scouting report says bunt. If the batter pulls back and swings, the shortstop covers third. Your job is to charge hard and take away the bunt."],
        rates:[85,8,25,15],concept:"On a sacrifice bunt, the third baseman charges hard. Get to the ball early for a chance to throw out the lead runner.",anim:"bunt",
        explSimple:["Charge in fast! If you get the ball quickly, you might throw out the lead runner.","Staying back lets the bunt just sit there. You have to come get it!","Don't hesitate — by the time you decide, the runner has already moved up.","Your job on a bunt play is to charge. Trust your teammates to cover if he swings."]},
      {pos:"firstBase",id:"sr3c",conceptTag:"bunt-defense",title:"First Base: Crash or Hold the Runner?",diff:2,cat:"fielder",ageMin:9,ageMax:99,
        options:["Charge toward home to field the bunt — leave first base open","Hold the runner at first, then react to the bunt after it's down","Charge hard, and if the ball goes to the third baseman, sprint back to cover first","Charge but pull up halfway to read the bunt direction"],
        best:2,explanations:["Charging is right, but you can't just abandon first base completely. Someone needs to cover first for the out. The second baseman should be rotating to cover, but you still need awareness of where the ball goes.","Holding the runner too long means the bunt dies in no-man's land. With a sacrifice bunt on, the runner is going to second regardless. Your priority is fielding the bunt or covering first, not holding the runner.","This is the smart play! Charge aggressively to field any bunt your way, but if the third baseman or pitcher fields it, peel back to cover first for the throw. You're covering both possibilities.","Pulling up halfway is hesitation. On bunt defense, you need to commit. Charge hard, and if someone else fields it, redirect to first. Halfway gets you nothing."],
        rates:[25,10,88,20],concept:"On a sacrifice bunt, the first baseman charges but stays aware. If someone else fields it, get back to cover first base for the throw.",anim:"bunt",
        explSimple:["Charge in, but remember someone needs to be at first base for the throw!","Don't just hold the runner — on a bunt play, you need to help field the ball.","Smart! Charge to help, but if someone else gets it, run back to first for the throw.","Don't hesitate — commit to charging, then adjust based on who fields the bunt."]},
      {pos:"batter",id:"sr3d",conceptTag:"bunt-re24",title:"Batter: Lay Down the Bunt",diff:2,cat:"batter",ageMin:9,ageMax:99,
        options:["Bunt it hard toward third base to move the runner and maybe beat it out","Bunt it softly down the first-base line — away from the charging third baseman","Try to push a bunt past the pitcher toward second base","Pull back and swing away — surprise them"],
        best:1,explanations:["Bunting hard toward third is risky. The third baseman is charging directly at you, so a hard bunt goes right to him. He fields it, throws to second, maybe turns two. A soft bunt AWAY from the charge is much smarter.","This is the correct sacrifice technique! Bunt softly down the first-base line, away from the charging third baseman and pitcher. This forces the first baseman or catcher to field it, and by then the runner has second base easily. You're out, but the runner is in scoring position. Fun fact: a sacrifice bunt with a runner on first costs about 0.23 expected runs compared to swinging away. But in a tie game in the 7th, moving the runner to scoring position is worth more than those numbers suggest because of win probability.","Bunting toward second base is extremely difficult to control and usually results in a ball going right back to the pitcher. The pitcher is the closest fielder and will grab it for an easy play. Keep the bunt toward the baselines.","Swinging away when the bunt sign is on means ignoring your coach's strategy. The whole defense is set up for a bunt — the third baseman is charging, the first baseman is charging. If you swing and miss, the runner might get thrown out. Execute the play your team needs."],
        rates:[15,88,10,12],concept:"On a sacrifice bunt, bunt softly away from the charging defenders. Down the first-base line is usually safest.",anim:"bunt",
        explSimple:["Bunting hard toward the charging third baseman is like throwing it right to him!","Perfect! Bunt it softly down the other side, away from the fielders running at you.","Bunting toward the pitcher usually means he grabs it for an easy out at second.","Your coach called a bunt for a reason. Surprise swings can mess up the whole plan."]}
    ]},
  {id:"sr4",title:"Extra-Base Hit to the Gap",emoji:"🏃",color:"#f97316",diff:2,
    situation:{inning:"Top 5",outs:1,count:"0-0",runners:[1],score:[1,2]},
    desc:"A line drive splits the outfielders into the left-center gap! The runner on first is off and running. Can the defense limit the damage?",
    debrief:"The ball split the outfielders into the left-center gap. The center fielder sprinted to the ball, set his feet, and threw a strong one-hopper to the shortstop, who had sprinted out to be the relay man — arms up, lined up between the outfielder and home plate. The shortstop caught the relay and fired home. The baserunner rounded third hard, read the relay throw coming in strong and on-line, and held at third. Smart aggression — he pressured the defense without running into an out.",
    teamworkTakeaway:"The relay system only works when everyone does their specific job: the outfielder hits the relay man, the relay man lines up correctly, and the baserunner reads the throw before committing. The ball moves faster than any runner — that's why the relay exists.",
    questions:[
      {pos:"centerField",id:"sr4a",conceptTag:"relay-double-cut",title:"Center Fielder: Get the Ball In",diff:2,cat:"fielder",ageMin:9,ageMax:99,
        options:["Chase the ball down, pick it up, and throw a rainbow to home plate","Get to the ball quickly and hit the cutoff man in the chest","Pick up the ball and hold it — don't throw to the wrong base","Run the ball in toward the infield yourself"],
        best:1,explanations:["A long throw from the gap almost never reaches home on a fly, because even if it does, it's offline and everyone advances. Hit the relay man and let the infield make the right play. The relay system exists for a reason.","Exactly right! Get to the ball quickly, set your feet, and throw a strong one-hopper to the relay man's chest. The relay man can then redirect home, to third, or wherever the play is. This is the fastest way to get the ball where it needs to go. A throw from deep center to home is about 300+ feet. Even elite arms lose accuracy at that distance. The relay system breaks it into two 150-foot throws — faster and more accurate.","Holding the ball in the gap is the worst thing an outfielder can do. Every second you hold it, runners advance. Get the ball to the relay man immediately — even if you're not sure where the play is, the relay man will redirect.","Running the ball in takes forever, since you're in the deepest part of the outfield, and the runners are circling bases. Throw it to the relay man — the ball travels faster than you do."],
        rates:[12,88,5,8],concept:"On extra-base hits, the outfielder's job is to hit the relay man quickly. Don't try hero throws to home from deep in the gap.",anim:"throwHome",
        explSimple:["Long throws from deep in the outfield almost never reach home. Use the cutoff man!","Hit the relay man in the chest and let the infield direct the play.","Never hold the ball in the outfield — every second you wait, runners move up.","The ball is much faster than you. Throw it, don't run it in!"]},
      {pos:"shortstop",id:"sr4b",conceptTag:"relay-double-cut",title:"Shortstop: Be the Relay",diff:2,cat:"fielder",ageMin:9,ageMax:99,
        options:["Run to a spot between the outfielder and home plate, arms up, calling for the ball","Stay near second base in case there's a play on the batter","Run to the outfield to help the center fielder pick up the ball","Stand still and let the second baseman be the cutoff man"],
        best:0,explanations:["You're the relay man on balls hit to left-center! Sprint to a spot in line between the center fielder and home plate, put both arms up high so the outfielder can see you, and call loud. Catch the throw and redirect it to the right base. The relay man should position about 150 feet from home plate, in a direct line between the outfielder and home. Arms up high — you're the outfielder's target.","Second base isn't the priority play. The runner from first is heading to third or home. Your job is to be the relay connection between the outfield and the infield. The second baseman can cover second.","Never run toward the outfield to help. You're needed in the relay chain. Running out there creates a gap in the infield and doesn't help the outfielder, who needs to throw to you, not hand it to you.","The shortstop is the relay man on balls hit to left-center and deep center. The second baseman covers the bag. Each player has a specific role in the relay system."],
        rates:[88,10,5,15],concept:"On a ball in the left-center gap, the shortstop is the lead relay man. Line up between the outfielder and home plate with arms up.",anim:"throwHome",
        explSimple:["Run out, line up with the outfielder and home plate, put your arms up, and call for it!","Second base isn't the most important play here. Be the relay to home!","Don't run toward the outfield — you need to be in the middle to relay the throw.","You're the relay man here, not the second baseman. Each player has a job."]},
      {pos:"baserunner",id:"sr4c",conceptTag:"baserunning-rates",title:"Runner on First: How Far Do You Go?",diff:2,cat:"baserunner",ageMin:9,ageMax:99,
        options:["Run hard and try to score from first on the hit to the gap","Run to third, round the bag hard, and read the relay throw before deciding on home","Stop at second — don't risk getting thrown out","Run to third and stop — don't be greedy, take the sure base"],
        best:1,explanations:["Trying to score from first on every gap hit is risky. If the outfielder gets to the ball quickly and the relay is clean, you'll be thrown out at home. You need to see the play develop before committing to score.","Smart and aggressive! Round third hard so the defense thinks you're going, but read the relay throw. If the cutoff man bobbles it or throws to the wrong base, go. If the relay is clean and on line, hold at third. This puts maximum pressure on the defense. Runners go from first to third successfully about 28% of the time on singles — but on extra-base hits to the gap, third base is almost automatic. The question is whether to try for home.","Stopping at second on a ball in the gap with one out is too conservative. You should be able to reach third easily on a hit to the gap with a head start from first. Take the extra base.","Third base is a great outcome, but stopping without even looking is leaving a potential run on the table. Round the bag and read the throw — you might be able to score if the defense makes any mistake."],
        rates:[20,88,10,35],concept:"Round third aggressively on a gap hit and read the relay throw. Put pressure on the defense but don't run into an out.",anim:"score",
        explSimple:["Trying to score every time is risky. Read the throw first!","Round third hard and watch the throw. If they mess up, go home. If not, stay at third.","Stopping at second on a gap hit is too safe. You can make it to third easily.","At least round the bag and look! You might be able to score if they bobble the throw."]}
    ]},
  {id:"sr5",title:"Full Count Showdown",emoji:"⚡",color:"#a855f7",diff:2,
    situation:{inning:"Bot 8",outs:2,count:"3-2",runners:[2],score:[5,5]},
    desc:"Tie game, 8th inning, two outs, runner on second, full count. This at-bat decides the game. Three perspectives, one moment.",
    debrief:"Full count, two outs, tie game. The pitcher trusted his best pitch — a fastball on the corner — and threw it with conviction. The batter took the championship approach: protect the plate, foul off tough pitches, put hittable ones in play. The manager had already sent the runner from second, knowing there was no downside on a full count with two outs. The batter lined a single to right, and the runner scored from second easily with his head start. Ballgame.",
    teamworkTakeaway:"In high-leverage moments, every role simplifies: the pitcher competes with his best stuff, the batter refuses to go down without a fight, and the manager makes sure the runners are in motion. Trust, aggression, and awareness win these moments.",
    questions:[
      {pos:"pitcher",id:"sr5a",conceptTag:"count-leverage",title:"Pitcher: The Payoff Pitch",diff:2,cat:"pitcher",ageMin:9,ageMax:99,
        options:["Throw your best pitch — fastball on the black, let your stuff win","Nibble the corner with a breaking ball — get him to chase","Walk him intentionally and pitch to the next batter","Throw the fastball right down the middle — just throw a strike"],
        best:0,explanations:["Trust your best pitch! At 3-2 with two outs, throw your strongest offering with conviction. A well-located fastball on the corner is a pitch you can be proud of win or lose. Compete with your best. At a 3-2 count, the batting average is .230 with an OBP of .350. The count is basically neutral — neither side has a clear edge. That's why your best pitch with conviction is the right call.","Nibbling at 3-2 is how walks happen, because a breaking ball needs perfect location, and if it misses, it's ball four. Your best fastball in a good spot gives you the most margin for error and the best chance at a strike.","Walking him to load second and third with two outs just creates more runners to worry about — the next batter might be just as dangerous. Face this hitter with your best stuff.","Throwing down the middle at 3-2 in a tie game is surrender, which means you're giving the batter the best possible pitch to hit. Compete on the corner with your best pitch, not down the middle with a prayer."],
        rates:[85,25,12,10],concept:"At 3-2 with two outs, throw your best pitch with conviction. Trust your stuff and compete on the corner.",anim:"strike",
        explSimple:["Throw your best pitch with confidence! Trust your stuff and hit the corner.","Breaking balls at 3-2 might miss for ball four. Your fastball has more room for error.","Walking him just puts more runners out there. Face this guy with your best.","Don't throw it down the middle — that's too easy to hit in a big moment."]},
      {pos:"batter",id:"sr5b",conceptTag:"count-leverage",title:"Batter: Tie Game, Full Count",diff:2,cat:"batter",ageMin:9,ageMax:99,
        options:["Sit on fastball — he's going to challenge you with his best","Protect the plate — anything close, foul it off or put it in play","Guess breaking ball and look to crush it if he hangs one","Take the pitch — hope for ball four and a free base"],
        best:1,explanations:["Sitting fastball at 3-2 with two outs is risky. If he throws a good breaking ball, you're frozen for strike three. With two outs and the game on the line, you need to be ready for anything.","This is the championship approach! At 3-2 with two outs, anything close you have to fight off. Foul off the tough pitches, put the hittable ones in play. The runner on second is going on the pitch — even a single wins it. Don't let the umpire decide your fate. At 3-2, the batting average is .230, but the OBP jumps to .350 because of walks. Protecting the plate keeps both outcomes alive — you can get a hit OR draw the walk.","Guessing breaking ball at 3-2 with two outs is a gamble. If he comes fastball, you're behind it. In this spot, protect and react — don't guess.","Taking 3-2 with two outs and the game on the line? That's letting the umpire decide the game. If it's close, he rings you up and you walk back to the dugout without swinging. Battle!"],
        rates:[25,88,15,8],concept:"At 3-2 with two outs, protect the plate. Fight off tough pitches and put hittable ones in play. Don't let the umpire end your day.",anim:"hit",
        explSimple:["If you only look for a fastball and he throws a curve, you'll strike out looking.","Fight off anything close! Foul off the tough ones, hit the good ones. Don't go down without swinging.","Guessing one pitch type is too risky with two outs. Be ready for everything.","Don't take a 3-2 pitch with two outs — if the umpire calls it a strike, the game is over!"]},
      {pos:"manager",id:"sr5c",conceptTag:"win-probability",title:"Manager: Call the Play",diff:2,cat:"manager",ageMin:9,ageMax:99,
        options:["Send the runner on the pitch — he's going on a full count anyway","Call for the runner to hold — don't risk a caught stealing to end the inning","Call for a hit-and-run to guarantee the runner moves up","Signal the batter to bunt the runner to third"],
        best:0,explanations:["With a full count and two outs, the runner should be going on the pitch automatically. If the batter walks, the runner is safe at third. If the batter makes contact, the runner has a huge head start to score. There's almost no downside. With two outs and a full count, there's zero risk in sending the runner. Ball four = free advance. Strikeout = inning over regardless. Contact = huge head start. It's a free play.","Holding the runner at second with a full count and two outs wastes a free opportunity. On ball four, the runner only advances to third instead of scoring position. On a hit, he might not score from second but would from a running start. Let him go.","A hit-and-run at 3-2 with two outs is basically the same as sending the runner since he should be going anyway. But calling it a hit-and-run puts pressure on the batter to swing at anything, even ball four. Just send the runner and let the batter compete.","Bunting with two outs makes zero sense. A bunt out ends the inning. You need a hit, walk, or error to score. Let the batter swing."],
        rates:[88,12,30,3],concept:"With a full count and two outs, send the runner. Ball four advances him, a hit gives him a head start, and a strikeout ends the inning regardless.",anim:"steal",
        explSimple:["On a full count with two outs, the runner should always go. If it's ball four, he moves up free!","Holding the runner wastes a free chance to advance. Let him go!","At 3-2, the runner is going anyway. No need for a special hit-and-run call.","Never bunt with two outs — a bunt out ends the inning!"]}
    ]},
  {id:"sr6",title:"Squeeze Play Alert",emoji:"🤫",color:"#eab308",diff:2,
    situation:{inning:"Bot 7",outs:1,count:"1-1",runners:[3],score:[2,3]},
    desc:"Runner on third, one out, down by one late in the game. The squeeze play is on! But the defense is watching.",
    debrief:"The squeeze was on. The runner on third broke for home as the pitcher started his delivery. The batter squared late — at the last possible moment — to keep the element of surprise. He bunted everything, getting the bat on a tough pitch and rolling it up the first-base line. The run scored. On the defensive side, the third baseman had been watching the runner's lead, saw him break early, and yelled 'SQUEEZE!' — but the call came just a fraction too late for the pitcher to adjust. Execution beats reaction.",
    teamworkTakeaway:"The squeeze play is baseball's most dramatic gamble. The runner commits blindly, the batter MUST make contact, and the defense has to recognize it in real-time. The offense wins through timing and commitment; the defense wins through recognition and communication.",
    questions:[
      {pos:"batter",id:"sr6a",conceptTag:"squeeze-play",title:"Batter: Execute the Squeeze",diff:2,cat:"batter",ageMin:9,ageMax:99,
        options:["Square around early to show bunt — get set before the pitch arrives","Wait until the pitcher commits to home, then square late and bunt anything","Only bunt if it's a strike — don't bunt a bad pitch","Pull back and swing if the pitch is hittable"],
        best:1,explanations:["Squaring early on a squeeze tips off the defense! The pitcher and catcher see you bunting and can throw a pitchout or high-and-tight. The whole point of a squeeze is surprise. Wait as long as possible to show your hand.","This is textbook squeeze execution! On a suicide squeeze, the runner is going on the pitch. You MUST bunt the ball no matter what. Square late so the defense can't react, and get the bat on the ball. Any bunt on the ground scores the run. On a suicide squeeze, the runner commits the moment the pitcher starts his delivery. If you don't bunt the ball, the catcher has it and the runner is out by 20 feet. That's why you MUST get the bat on the ball — no matter where the pitch is.","On a suicide squeeze, the runner breaks for home as the pitch is thrown. If you take a bad pitch, the catcher has the ball and the runner is a dead duck at home. You MUST bunt everything — that's the deal with a squeeze.","Pulling back and swinging defeats the purpose of the squeeze. The runner is sprinting home — if you swing and miss, he's out by 30 feet. If you hit a line drive, he might get doubled off third. Bunt!"],
        rates:[15,88,10,5],concept:"On a suicide squeeze, square late and bunt EVERYTHING. The runner is committed — you must get the bat on the ball.",anim:"bunt",
        explSimple:["Squaring early warns the defense! Wait until the last second to show the bunt.","Wait until the pitcher throws, then bunt it. The runner is already running, so you MUST bunt it!","You have to bunt no matter what — the runner is running home and counting on you!","Don't swing! The runner is sprinting home. A bunt is the only safe play."]},
      {pos:"pitcher",id:"sr6b",conceptTag:"squeeze-recognition",title:"Pitcher: Sniff Out the Squeeze",diff:2,cat:"pitcher",ageMin:9,ageMax:99,
        options:["If you see the batter square, throw a high-and-tight fastball to make the bunt impossible","Pitch normally and trust your fielders to make the play","Step off the rubber immediately if you suspect a squeeze","Throw a pitchout if the runner is getting a big lead off third"],
        best:0,explanations:["If you recognize the squeeze — the runner breaking early, the batter squaring — throw high and tight. A high-and-tight pitch is nearly impossible to bunt fair. The batter either misses or pops it up, and the runner is hung out to dry between third and home. A pitch up and in is nearly impossible to bunt down onto the ground. The bat angle required to bunt a high-inside pitch almost guarantees a popup or foul ball — exactly what you want when the runner is committed.","Pitching normally with no awareness of the squeeze means the batter lays down an easy bunt and the run scores. You need to read the play and react. The squeeze is the offense's most aggressive weapon — defend it.","Stepping off the rubber works if you suspect a squeeze BEFORE committing to home. But once you start your delivery, you must go to the plate. Reading the signs early is better than reacting late.","A pitchout can work if you call it before the pitch, but you need coordination with the catcher. If you recognize the squeeze during your delivery, the high-and-tight pitch is the best in-the-moment weapon."],
        rates:[88,10,30,25],concept:"If you recognize a squeeze, throw high and tight. It's nearly impossible to bunt a pitch up and in, and the runner is dead.",anim:"bunt",
        explSimple:["If you see the squeeze coming, throw it high and inside — that's almost impossible to bunt!","You can't just pitch normally — if the squeeze is on and you ignore it, the run scores easily.","Stepping off works if you catch it early, but a high-and-tight pitch is the best reaction.","A pitchout needs to be planned ahead of time. High-and-tight works in the moment."]},
      {pos:"thirdBase",id:"sr6c",conceptTag:"squeeze-recognition",title:"Third Base: Watch the Runner",diff:2,cat:"fielder",ageMin:9,ageMax:99,
        options:["Watch the runner at third — if he breaks early, yell 'SQUEEZE!' to alert the pitcher","Charge in toward home as the pitch is thrown to be ready for the bunt","Stay back at third base in case the batter pulls back and swings","Ignore the runner and focus on the batter's hands"],
        best:0,explanations:["Your eyes are the defense's early warning system! The runner at third will give away the squeeze by breaking early or getting an unusually big lead. If you spot it, yell 'SQUEEZE!' so the pitcher and catcher can react. Communication wins games.","Charging in before you know it's a bunt leaves third base open. If the batter swings away and hits a ground ball, nobody covers third and the runner might score anyway on a passed ball or error.","Staying back doesn't help anyone. If the squeeze is on, you need to charge once the bunt is down to field it. But your first job is reading the runner and communicating to your battery.","Ignoring the runner is ignoring the biggest clue! The runner's movement tells you whether a squeeze is on before the batter even shows bunt. Watch the runner, then react to the batter."],
        rates:[88,20,12,10],concept:"The third baseman is the squeeze alarm. Watch the runner's lead and break — yell 'SQUEEZE!' to alert the battery if you see it.",anim:"bunt",
        explSimple:["Watch the runner! If he starts running home early, yell 'SQUEEZE!' to warn your team.","Don't charge in too early — you might leave third base wide open.","Staying back doesn't help. Your job is to read the play and tell your pitcher.","The runner gives away the squeeze before the batter does. Watch his lead!"]}
    ]},
  {id:"sr7",title:"Rundown Chaos",emoji:"🔄",color:"#6366f1",diff:2,
    situation:{inning:"Top 3",outs:0,count:"0-0",runners:[1,3],score:[0,1]},
    desc:"Runners on first and third, nobody out. The runner on first gets caught in a rundown between first and second! But the runner on third is lurking. What does everyone do?",
    debrief:"Runners on first and third, and the runner on first got caught in a rundown. The first baseman chased him toward second — ball held high, running hard — while keeping one eye on the runner at third. The shortstop closed the gap from the second-base side, shortening the runway. When the runner at third saw the ball thrown toward second (away from home), he broke for the plate. The first baseman, alert to this exact situation, threw home instead. The catcher applied the tag. One out in the rundown, and the defense kept the runner at third honest.",
    teamworkTakeaway:"In a first-and-third rundown, the defense has to solve two problems at once: get the out on the caught runner AND watch the runner at third. The runner at third has to time his break for when the ball moves away from home. Both sides are thinking two moves ahead.",
    questions:[
      {pos:"firstBase",id:"sr7a",conceptTag:"rundown-mechanics",title:"First Base: Chase and Tag",diff:2,cat:"fielder",ageMin:9,ageMax:99,
        options:["Chase the runner toward second with the ball, throw when the runner from third commits to score","Run the runner back to first and tag him yourself — don't risk a throw","Chase toward second and make as many throws as possible to tire out the runner","Throw to second immediately and let them handle the rundown"],
        best:0,explanations:["The key in a first-and-third rundown is keeping the runner at third honest. Chase toward second (pushing the caught runner away from first), and keep one eye on the runner at third. The moment that runner breaks for home, throw home to get the more important out. If he stays, keep running the caught runner back toward a tag. The #1 rule of rundowns: get the out in as few throws as possible. Every throw is a chance for an error, and every second gives the runner at third more time to read the play.","Running the runner back to first means you still have runners on first and third, because you haven't gained anything — the situation is the same as before. Chase toward second to at least force progress.","Making many throws is how errors happen in rundowns, since every throw is a chance for a bad throw, a missed catch, or an advancing runner. The rule is: get the out in as few throws as possible.","Throwing to second immediately gives up control, because you want to run at the caught runner (ball in hand) and force the issue. The fielder with the ball dictates the rundown."],
        rates:[88,15,10,20],concept:"In a first-and-third rundown, chase toward second but watch the runner at third. If he breaks for home, throw home for the important out.",anim:"rundown",
        explSimple:["Chase toward second but keep watching the runner at third! If he runs home, throw there.","Running him back to first doesn't help — you're right back where you started.","Too many throws means more chances to make a mistake. Keep it simple.","Hold the ball and run at the runner. The player with the ball controls the rundown."]},
      {pos:"shortstop",id:"sr7b",conceptTag:"rundown-mechanics",title:"Shortstop: Receive and Tag",diff:2,cat:"fielder",ageMin:9,ageMax:99,
        options:["Stand at second base and wait for the throw from the first baseman","Move toward the runner being chased — close the gap so the tag comes sooner","Stay near your normal position and watch the runner at third","Run toward the pitcher's mound to create a throwing lane"],
        best:1,explanations:["Standing at the bag is too far away. The rundown should end between bases, not at the bag. Move toward the incoming runner so when you receive the throw, you're close enough for an immediate tag. Shorter distance = faster tag.","Exactly! Close the gap between you and the runner being chased. When the first baseman throws, you receive it close to the runner and apply the tag immediately. The shorter the runway, the fewer chances for the runner to escape or the other runner to steal home. In a well-executed rundown, the tag should happen within one throw — two at most. Closing the gap makes that possible. Standing at the bag means 2-3 throws, which means 2-3 chances for something to go wrong.","Watching the runner at third is important, but that's the catcher's and first baseman's primary job. Your job is to receive the throw and make the tag on the caught runner. Get involved in the rundown.","Going to the mound creates confusion and takes you out of position. The throwing lane is between first and second — that's where you need to be."],
        rates:[20,88,15,5],concept:"In a rundown, close the gap toward the runner so the tag happens quickly. Don't stand on the bag — move toward the action.",anim:"rundown",
        explSimple:["Move toward the runner! The closer you are, the quicker you can tag him.","Standing on the bag is too far. Close the distance and make the tag easy.","Your job is to catch the throw and tag the runner. Don't just watch!","Stay between first and second where the rundown is happening."]},
      {pos:"baserunner",id:"sr7c",conceptTag:"first-third",title:"Runner on Third: When to Go",diff:2,cat:"baserunner",ageMin:9,ageMax:99,
        options:["Break for home the moment the rundown starts — they're distracted","Wait and watch — only go home when the throw goes TOWARD second base (away from you)","Stay at third no matter what — don't risk getting thrown out on a heads-up play","Bluff toward home to draw a throw, then scramble back to third"],
        best:1,explanations:["Breaking immediately is too predictable. A smart defense expects this and will throw home right away. You need to time it with the right throw — when the ball is going toward second and the fielder's momentum is carrying him away from you.","Perfect read! When the ball is thrown toward second base, the fielders are moving away from home plate. Their momentum is wrong for a quick throw home. That's your window. Go hard and score before they can redirect.","Staying at third no matter what wastes a golden opportunity. The defense is occupied with the rundown. If you time it right, this is a free run. Being too passive is as bad as being too aggressive.","Bluffing can work but is risky. If you fake too hard and get caught too far down the line, you're in your own rundown and now both runners might be out. Wait for the right throw and GO with full commitment."],
        rates:[15,88,8,25],concept:"In a first-and-third rundown, the runner at third goes home when the throw goes toward second. The defense's momentum takes them away from you.",anim:"score",
        explSimple:["Going right away is too easy for the defense to catch. Wait for the right moment!","When the ball goes toward second base, the fielders are moving away from you. That's when to go!","Don't just stand there — this is a great chance to score if you time it right.","Bluffing is risky — you might get caught in between. When you go, commit fully!"]}
    ]},
  {id:"sr8",title:"Tag-Up Play at the Warning Track",emoji:"🏷️",color:"#ec4899",diff:2,
    situation:{inning:"Bot 5",outs:1,count:"0-0",runners:[3],score:[1,2]},
    desc:"A deep fly ball to center field! The runner on third has to decide: tag up and try to score, or stay put?",
    debrief:"Deep fly ball to center. The center fielder camped under it, caught it cleanly with momentum toward home, crow-hopped, and fired a throw on a line toward the plate. The baserunner on third tagged up the instant the ball hit leather, read the outfielder's throw, and saw it was strong and on-line. The third base coach read the same thing and held the runner. Smart play — a run scoring on a sacrifice fly is only valuable if you actually score. Running into the tag wastes the out.",
    teamworkTakeaway:"Tag-up plays are a three-way calculation: the outfielder's depth and arm strength, the runner's speed and read, and the third base coach's judgment. The coach sees the whole play — the runner trusts the coach, and the outfielder makes his best throw. Everyone reads the same situation differently based on their role.",
    questions:[
      {pos:"centerField",id:"sr8a",conceptTag:"of-depth-arm-value",title:"Center Fielder: Catch and Throw Home",diff:2,cat:"fielder",ageMin:9,ageMax:99,
        options:["Catch the ball on the run and throw home in one motion","Camp under the ball, catch it, then crow hop and throw home with everything you've got","Let the ball bounce and play it on a hop to keep the runner at third","Catch the ball and throw to second base to prevent the batter from advancing"],
        best:1,explanations:["Catching on the run sounds fast but it's inaccurate — a rushed throw from an off-balance position usually sails or bounces. Plant your feet, catch it cleanly, and make a strong accurate throw. Accuracy beats speed every time.","This is the right technique! Camp under the ball, catch it cleanly with momentum toward home, crow hop for power, and deliver a strong throw to the catcher on a line. The crow hop transfers energy from your legs into the throw for maximum velocity and accuracy. The crow hop can add 5-10 mph to your throw — that's the difference between beating the runner and not.","Letting the ball bounce on a fly ball with a runner tagging is a terrible mistake, which means the runner tags and scores easily while you're playing a groundball. Always catch the fly ball and throw.","The play is at home! Throwing to second base when there's a runner tagging from third is giving up the run to prevent the batter from reaching second, because that's the wrong priority."],
        rates:[20,88,3,8],concept:"On a sacrifice fly attempt, catch cleanly with momentum toward home, crow hop, and throw on a line. Accuracy beats panic.",anim:"throwHome",
        explSimple:["Catching on the run makes your throw wild. Plant your feet and throw accurately.","Camp under it, catch it, take a strong step, and throw a laser home!","Never let a fly ball bounce when a runner is tagging up — they'll score easily!","The runner is going home! Throw home, not to second base."]},
      {pos:"baserunner",id:"sr8b",conceptTag:"tag-up",title:"Runner on Third: Tag and Go?",diff:2,cat:"baserunner",ageMin:9,ageMax:99,
        options:["Tag up and go home on any fly ball to the outfield — all of them are deep enough","Tag up, watch the catch, and read the outfielder's throw before committing","Only tag on fly balls to left or right field — center field is too close to home","Don't tag up — wait for a base hit to score safely"],
        best:1,explanations:["Not every fly ball is deep enough to tag on. A shallow fly to center or left means the throw home will beat you. You need to read the depth, the outfielder's arm strength, and the accuracy of the throw before committing.","Smart baserunning! Touch the base, watch the catch, and read the throw. If the outfielder is deep and the throw is weak or offline, GO. If the throw is strong and on line, HOLD. Your first few steps tell you everything — hit the base and go hard, then decide. Runners score from third on sacrifice flies about 88% of the time overall. But that drops significantly on shallow flies or throws from strong-armed outfielders. Reading the depth is what keeps that success rate high.","Center field can actually be a good tag-up if the ball is deep enough. Don't rule out any position — read the depth and the arm. Some center fielders have weak arms, and warning-track catches are deep enough to tag on.","Not tagging up with one out and runner on third is leaving a run on the table. Sacrifice flies are one of the most common ways to score from third. You have to be aggressive and smart."],
        rates:[15,88,20,8],concept:"Tag up on deep fly balls by reading the outfielder's depth and throw. Touch the base on the catch and read as you go.",anim:"score",
        explSimple:["Not every fly ball is deep enough. Watch how far back the fielder is before you go.","Touch the base, watch the catch, and then decide if the throw will beat you or not.","Don't rule out center field tags — if the catch is deep enough, you can score!","Sacrifice flies are one of the best ways to score. Be ready to go!"]},
      {pos:"manager",id:"sr8c",conceptTag:"tag-up",title:"Third Base Coach: Send or Hold?",diff:2,cat:"manager",ageMin:9,ageMax:99,
        options:["Send every runner on every fly ball — put pressure on the defense","Watch the outfielder's catch and arm angle, then decide to wave the runner home or hold him","Always hold the runner — don't risk the out when you're only down one","Send the runner regardless, but have him slide to avoid the tag"],
        best:1,explanations:["Sending everyone on everything gets runners thrown out. Some outfielders have cannons. Your job as third base coach is to read the play and make smart decisions. Aggressive doesn't mean reckless.","This is elite coaching! Read the catch depth, the outfielder's momentum and arm angle, and the accuracy of the throw. If the outfielder is falling backward or the throw is off-line, wave the runner home. If the throw is strong and accurate, hold him at third with one out.","Always holding is too conservative. Down by one run with one out, a sacrifice fly ties the game. That's a situation where you should be looking to send the runner on any catchable deep fly. Make smart reads, not blanket rules.","Telling a runner to slide doesn't fix a bad send. If the throw beats the runner by five steps, no slide will help. The decision to send or hold is the important part — the slide is a last resort, not a strategy."],
        rates:[12,88,15,10],concept:"The third base coach reads the outfielder's depth, momentum, and arm before sending the runner. Smart aggression beats blind aggression.",anim:"score",
        explSimple:["Don't send everyone every time — some outfielders have really strong arms!","Watch the catch and the throw. If the throw looks weak or offline, send the runner. If not, hold him.","Don't always hold either! Sacrifice flies are a great way to tie the game.","Sliding doesn't help if the runner is out by a mile. The decision to go or hold is what matters."]}
    ]},
  // ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  // ROOKIE SITUATION SETS (diff:1, ages 6-10, 2 questions each)
  // ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  {id:"sr1r",title:"Bases Loaded Jam (Rookie)",emoji:"🔥",color:"#ef4444",diff:1,
    situation:{inning:"Bot 6",outs:1,count:"1-2",runners:[1,2,3],score:[3,4]},
    desc:"Bases loaded! Runners on every base. The pitcher and baserunner both have important jobs. Can you help?",
    debrief:"The pitcher threw a low pitch and the batter hit a ground ball. The runner on third was smart — he watched where the ball went before running home. The team worked together!",
    teamworkTakeaway:"The pitcher and the baserunner both have to do their jobs for the team to succeed.",
    questions:[
      {pos:"pitcher",id:"sr1ra",conceptTag:"pitch-sequencing",title:"Pitcher: Keep It Low!",diff:1,cat:"pitcher",ageMin:6,ageMax:10,
        options:["Throw the ball low to get a ground ball","Throw the ball as hard as you can up high","Walk the batter on purpose","Throw it right down the middle"],
        best:0,explanations:["A ground ball can turn into a double play and end the inning! After all, keep the ball low.","High pitches might get hit hard with bases loaded, since ground balls are safer.","Walking in a run on purpose is almost always a bad idea.","Don't throw it right down the middle — that's too easy to hit hard, since it gives you the best chance of success."],
        rates:[90,40,15,25],concept:"When bases are loaded, throw the ball low to get a ground ball. Ground balls can become double plays!",anim:"doubleplay"},
      {pos:"baserunner",id:"sr1rb",conceptTag:"baserunning-rates",title:"Runner on Third: Watch the Ball!",diff:1,cat:"baserunner",ageMin:6,ageMax:10,
        options:["Run home on every ground ball no matter what","Watch where the ball goes first, then decide to run or stay","Tag up on any fly ball and run home","Stay on third base and wait for a hit"],
        best:1,explanations:["Don't just run on every ground ball — some are hit right at the catcher or pitcher!","Smart! Read where the ball goes first. If it's hit to the right side, you have time to score.","Only tag up on deep fly balls. Shallow ones mean the throw will beat you home.","Don't just stand there! With bases loaded, there are lots of chances to score."],
        rates:[10,92,12,8],concept:"Watch where the ball goes before you run! If it's hit far away, you can score. If it's hit close, stay put.",anim:"score"}
    ]},
  {id:"sr2r",title:"Steal Attempt! (Rookie)",emoji:"💨",color:"#06b6d4",diff:1,
    situation:{inning:"Top 4",outs:0,count:"1-1",runners:[1],score:[2,2]},
    desc:"A fast runner is trying to steal second base! The pitcher and catcher need to stop him. Can they do it?",
    debrief:"The pitcher threw the ball to the catcher really fast. The catcher caught it and threw it quickly to second base. The runner was out! Teamwork stopped the steal.",
    teamworkTakeaway:"The pitcher throws fast and the catcher throws fast — together they can stop a base stealer!",
    questions:[
      {pos:"pitcher",id:"sr2ra",conceptTag:"steal-window",title:"Pitcher: Be Quick!",diff:1,cat:"pitcher",ageMin:6,ageMax:10,
        options:["Throw the ball to the catcher as fast as you can — use a slide step","Use your full windup and throw really hard","Step off the rubber and look at the runner","Hold the ball for a really long time to freeze the runner"],
        best:0,explanations:["A slide step gets the ball to your catcher faster so they can throw the runner out!.","A full windup is too slow with a runner on base, because they'll steal easily.","Stepping off doesn't help once the runner is already going — just throw fast.","Holding the ball too long can be a balk! Since just deliver it quickly."],
        rates:[90,15,40,25],concept:"When a runner is stealing, throw the ball to your catcher quickly! A slide step is faster than a big windup.",anim:"steal"},
      {pos:"catcher",id:"sr2rb",conceptTag:"steal-window",title:"Catcher: Throw It Fast!",diff:1,cat:"catcher",ageMin:6,ageMax:10,
        options:["Catch the ball, get it out of your glove fast, and throw to second base","Catch the ball, stand up all the way, then throw to second","Catch the ball and throw to first base","Catch the ball and fake a throw to trick the runner"],
        best:0,explanations:["Catch it, get it out of your glove fast, and throw to where the fielder is waiting!","Standing up takes too long! The runner will be safe by the time you throw.","Throw to the side where the fielder is catching it and making the tag.","A pump fake just wastes time when the runner is sprinting. Throw it!"],
        rates:[92,8,5,10],concept:"When a runner is stealing, catch the ball and throw it to second base as fast as you can!",anim:"steal"}
    ]},
  {id:"sr3r",title:"Bunt Play! (Rookie)",emoji:"🎯",color:"#22c55e",diff:1,
    situation:{inning:"Bot 7",outs:0,count:"0-0",runners:[1],score:[3,3]},
    desc:"The coach wants a bunt to move the runner! The batter needs to bunt well, and the pitcher needs to make it hard. Who wins?",
    debrief:"The batter bunted the ball softly away from the fielders. The runner moved to second base. The pitcher tried to throw a high pitch to make it hard, but the batter got it down!",
    teamworkTakeaway:"The batter listens to the coach's plan, and the pitcher tries to stop it — both are doing their jobs!",
    questions:[
      {pos:"batter",id:"sr3ra",conceptTag:"bunt-re24",title:"Batter: Bunt It Right!",diff:1,cat:"batter",ageMin:6,ageMax:10,
        options:["Bunt it hard toward the third baseman running at you","Bunt it softly down the first-base line, away from the fielders","Bunt it right back at the pitcher","Forget the bunt and swing away"],
        best:1,explanations:["Bunting hard toward the charging third baseman is like throwing it right to him!, since it gives you the best chance of success.","Perfect! Remember, you bunt it softly down the other side, away from the fielders running at you.","Bunting toward the pitcher usually means he grabs it for an easy out at second.","Your coach called a bunt for a reason, which means surprise swings can mess up the whole plan."],
        rates:[25,90,15,40],concept:"When you bunt, bunt it softly away from the fielders! Don't bunt it right at someone running toward you.",anim:"bunt"},
      {pos:"pitcher",id:"sr3rb",conceptTag:"bunt-defense",title:"Pitcher: Make It Hard to Bunt!",diff:1,cat:"pitcher",ageMin:6,ageMax:10,
        options:["Throw a high fastball — high pitches are hard to bunt","Throw it low — low pitches are easy to bunt","Throw it right down the middle — easy for the batter","Throw it inside to hit the batter"],
        best:0,explanations:["High pitches are really hard to bunt! They usually pop up or go foul.","Low pitches are actually easier to bunt. Don't help the bunter!","Don't throw it right down the middle — that's the easiest pitch to bunt.","Inside pitches might hit the batter and put another runner on base."],
        rates:[92,8,5,10],concept:"If someone is bunting, throw the ball up high! High pitches are really hard to bunt.",anim:"bunt"}
    ]},
  {id:"sr4r",title:"Ball in the Gap! (Rookie)",emoji:"🏃",color:"#f97316",diff:1,
    situation:{inning:"Top 5",outs:1,count:"0-0",runners:[1],score:[1,2]},
    desc:"The ball was hit between the outfielders! The center fielder needs to get the ball in, and the runner needs to decide how far to go!",
    debrief:"The center fielder picked up the ball and threw it to the relay man. The runner ran to third base and watched the throw before deciding to stay. Great teamwork!",
    teamworkTakeaway:"The outfielder throws to the relay man, and the runner watches the ball before deciding how far to go!",
    questions:[
      {pos:"centerField",id:"sr4ra",conceptTag:"relay-double-cut",title:"Center Fielder: Throw It In!",diff:1,cat:"fielder",ageMin:6,ageMax:10,
        options:["Try to throw the ball all the way home by yourself","Throw it to the relay man — he's closer and can pass it along","Hold the ball and run it in yourself","Pick up the ball and wait to see what happens"],
        best:1,explanations:["Long throws from deep in the outfield almost never reach home, because you use the cutoff man!","Hit the relay man in the chest and let the infield direct the play.","Never hold the ball in the outfield — every second you wait, runners move up.","The ball is much faster than you, since you throw it, don't run it in!"],
        rates:[25,90,15,40],concept:"When the ball is hit far away, throw it to the relay man! He's closer and can get it where it needs to go.",anim:"throwHome"},
      {pos:"baserunner",id:"sr4rb",conceptTag:"baserunning-rates",title:"Runner: How Far Do You Go?",diff:1,cat:"baserunner",ageMin:6,ageMax:10,
        options:["Run home as fast as you can no matter what","Run to third, look at the throw, then decide if you can score","Stop at second — that's far enough","Run to third and stop without looking"],
        best:1,explanations:["Trying to score every time is risky. Read the throw first!","Round third hard and watch the throw. If they mess up, go home. If not, stay at third.","Stopping at second on a gap hit is too safe. You can make it to third easily.","At least round the bag and look! You might be able to score if they bobble the throw."],
        rates:[10,92,8,15],concept:"Run hard to third base, then look at the throw! If the throw is bad, keep going. If it's good, stay at third.",anim:"score"}
    ]},
  {id:"sr5r",title:"Full Count! (Rookie)",emoji:"⚡",color:"#a855f7",diff:1,
    situation:{inning:"Bot 8",outs:2,count:"3-2",runners:[2],score:[5,5]},
    desc:"Three balls, two strikes! The pitcher needs to throw a good pitch, and the batter needs to be ready for anything!",
    debrief:"The pitcher threw his best pitch on the corner. The batter didn't give up — he fought off a tough pitch and hit a single to win the game! Both players gave it everything they had.",
    teamworkTakeaway:"On a full count, the pitcher throws his best and the batter fights to stay alive — that's what competing means!",
    questions:[
      {pos:"pitcher",id:"sr5ra",conceptTag:"count-leverage",title:"Pitcher: Make Your Best Pitch!",diff:1,cat:"pitcher",ageMin:6,ageMax:10,
        options:["Throw your best pitch on the corner — trust your stuff","Throw a tricky pitch that might miss for ball four","Walk him on purpose and pitch to someone else","Throw it right down the middle"],
        best:0,explanations:["Throw your best pitch with confidence! The reason is trust your stuff and hit the corner.","Breaking balls at 3-2 might miss for ball four, because your fastball has more room for error.","Walking him just puts more runners out there — face this guy with your best.","Don't throw it down the middle — that's too easy to hit in a big moment, which means the outcome won't be what you need."],
        rates:[90,40,15,25],concept:"On a full count, throw your best pitch! Don't try to be tricky — throw the pitch you're best at.",anim:"strike"},
      {pos:"batter",id:"sr5rb",conceptTag:"count-leverage",title:"Batter: Protect the Plate!",diff:1,cat:"batter",ageMin:6,ageMax:10,
        options:["Only swing if it's a fastball — guess what's coming","Swing at anything close — don't let the umpire call strike three","Guess curveball and swing really hard","Just stand there and hope for ball four"],
        best:1,explanations:["If you only look for a fastball and he throws a curve, you'll strike out looking.","Fight off anything close! Foul off the tough ones, hit the good ones. Don't go down without swinging.","Guessing one pitch type is too risky with two outs. Be ready for everything.","Don't take a 3-2 pitch with two outs — if the umpire calls it a strike, the game is over!"],
        rates:[10,92,8,5],concept:"On a full count with two outs, swing at anything close! Don't let the umpire end your turn.",anim:"hit"}
    ]},
  {id:"sr6r",title:"Squeeze Play! (Rookie)",emoji:"🤫",color:"#eab308",diff:1,
    situation:{inning:"Bot 7",outs:1,count:"1-1",runners:[3],score:[2,3]},
    desc:"The runner on third is going to try to score on a bunt! The batter must bunt, and the pitcher must try to stop it!",
    debrief:"The batter waited until the last second and bunted the ball. The runner scored from third! The pitcher tried to throw a high pitch, but the batter got the bat on it just in time.",
    teamworkTakeaway:"On a squeeze play, the runner trusts the batter to bunt, and the batter trusts the coach's call!",
    questions:[
      {pos:"batter",id:"sr6ra",conceptTag:"squeeze-play",title:"Batter: You Must Bunt!",diff:1,cat:"batter",ageMin:6,ageMax:10,
        options:["Show the bunt early so you're ready","Wait until the last second, then bunt the ball no matter where it is","Only bunt if it's a good pitch to hit","Pull back and swing instead"],
        best:1,explanations:["Squaring early warns the defense! After all, wait until the last second to show the bunt.","Wait until the pitcher throws, then bunt it, which means the runner is already running, so you MUST bunt it!","You have to bunt no matter what — the runner is running home and counting on you!.","Don't swing! The runner is sprinting home, because a bunt is the only safe play."],
        rates:[40,90,25,15],concept:"On a squeeze play, you HAVE to bunt the ball! The runner is already running home and counting on you!",anim:"bunt"},
      {pos:"pitcher",id:"sr6rb",conceptTag:"squeeze-recognition",title:"Pitcher: Stop the Squeeze!",diff:1,cat:"pitcher",ageMin:6,ageMax:10,
        options:["If you see the bunt coming, throw it high and inside — that's impossible to bunt","Just pitch normally and hope for the best","Step off the rubber and yell","Throw a really slow pitch"],
        best:0,explanations:["If you see the squeeze coming, throw it high and inside — that's almost impossible to bunt!","You can't just pitch normally — if the squeeze is on and you ignore it, the run scores easily.","Stepping off works if you catch it early, but a high-and-tight pitch is the best reaction.","A slow pitch gives the batter more time to bunt it. That helps the other team!"],
        rates:[92,8,12,5],concept:"If you see a squeeze play coming, throw the ball up high! High pitches are almost impossible to bunt!",anim:"bunt"}
    ]},
  {id:"sr7r",title:"Rundown! (Rookie)",emoji:"🔄",color:"#6366f1",diff:1,
    situation:{inning:"Top 3",outs:0,count:"0-0",runners:[1,3],score:[0,1]},
    desc:"A runner got caught between bases! The first baseman chases him, and the runner on third is watching for a chance to score!",
    debrief:"The first baseman chased the runner toward second base. The runner on third waited for the right moment and scored when the ball went away from home plate. Smart running!",
    teamworkTakeaway:"In a rundown, everyone has a job — the fielders chase and the runners look for chances!",
    questions:[
      {pos:"firstBase",id:"sr7ra",conceptTag:"rundown-mechanics",title:"First Base: Chase Him!",diff:1,cat:"fielder",ageMin:6,ageMax:10,
        options:["Chase the runner toward second, but watch the runner on third too","Run the runner back to first and tag him there","Throw the ball back and forth as many times as you can","Throw the ball to second right away and hope they get him"],
        best:0,explanations:["Chase toward second but keep watching the runner at third! Since if he runs home, throw there.","Running him back to first doesn't help — you're right back where you started, since it gives you the best chance of success.","Too many throws means more chances to make a mistake, since you keep it simple.","Hold the ball and run at the runner, because the player with the ball controls the rundown."],
        rates:[90,40,15,25],concept:"In a rundown, chase the runner but keep watching the other runners! They might try to score.",anim:"rundown"},
      {pos:"baserunner",id:"sr7rb",conceptTag:"first-third",title:"Runner on Third: When to Go!",diff:1,cat:"baserunner",ageMin:6,ageMax:10,
        options:["Run home right away when the rundown starts","Wait until the ball is thrown toward second base, then run home","Stay on third no matter what","Run halfway home and then run back"],
        best:1,explanations:["Going right away is too easy for the defense to catch. Wait for the right moment!","When the ball goes toward second base, the fielders are moving away from you. That's when to go!","Don't just stand there — this is a great chance to score if you time it right.","Bluffing is risky — you might get caught in between. When you go, commit fully!"],
        rates:[10,92,5,8],concept:"In a rundown, wait until the ball is thrown away from you, then run home! The fielders can't throw two ways at once.",anim:"score"}
    ]},
  {id:"sr8r",title:"Tag Up! (Rookie)",emoji:"🏷️",color:"#ec4899",diff:1,
    situation:{inning:"Bot 5",outs:1,count:"0-0",runners:[3],score:[1,2]},
    desc:"A deep fly ball to center field! The runner on third has to decide: tag up and try to score, or stay? The center fielder has to make a great throw!",
    debrief:"The center fielder caught the ball and made a strong throw home. The runner tagged up and watched the throw — it was too strong to beat, so he stayed at third. Smart play!",
    teamworkTakeaway:"The runner watches the throw before deciding to go, and the outfielder makes the best throw he can!",
    questions:[
      {pos:"baserunner",id:"sr8ra",conceptTag:"tag-up",title:"Runner: Should You Go?",diff:1,cat:"baserunner",ageMin:6,ageMax:10,
        options:["Run home on every fly ball — just go!","Touch third base, watch the catch, then decide if you can make it","Only run on fly balls to left or right field","Stay on third base and wait for a regular hit"],
        best:1,explanations:["Not every fly ball is deep enough — watch how far back the fielder is before you go.","Touch the base, watch the catch, and then decide if the throw will beat you or not.","Don't rule out center field tags — if the catch is deep enough, you can score!.","Sacrifice flies are one of the best ways to score, which means be ready to go!"],
        rates:[25,90,40,15],concept:"On a fly ball, touch your base and watch the catch. If the fielder is really far back, you can run home!",anim:"score"},
      {pos:"centerField",id:"sr8rb",conceptTag:"of-depth-arm-value",title:"Center Fielder: Make Your Throw!",diff:1,cat:"fielder",ageMin:6,ageMax:10,
        options:["Catch the ball while running and throw right away","Catch the ball, take a big step toward home, and throw it hard","Let the ball bounce and play the hop","Catch the ball and throw to second base instead"],
        best:1,explanations:["Catching on the run makes your throw wild. Plant your feet and throw accurately.","Camp under it, catch it, take a strong step, and throw a laser home!","Never let a fly ball bounce when a runner is tagging up — they'll score easily!","The runner is going home! Throw home, not to second base."],
        rates:[10,92,5,8],concept:"Catch the fly ball, take a big step toward home plate, and throw it as hard as you can! That's how you stop the runner.",anim:"throwHome"}
    ]},
  // ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  // ALL-STAR SITUATION SETS (diff:3, ages 12+, 4-5 questions each)
  // ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  {id:"sr1a3",title:"Bases Loaded Jam (All-Star)",emoji:"🔥",color:"#ef4444",diff:3,
    situation:{inning:"Bot 6",outs:1,count:"1-2",runners:[1,2,3],score:[3,4]},
    desc:"Bases loaded, one out, down by one in the 6th. The defense needs a double play. Every decision in the next 3 seconds determines the inning.",
    debrief:"The pitcher located a sinker low-and-away at 1-2, exactly where the catcher set up. RE24 with bases loaded and one out is 1.59 — a double play drops it to 0.11, a 1.48-run swing. The batter grounded to short, who fed the ball to second with the proper 6-4-3 footwork — chest-to-chest transfer, right foot on the bag, pivot and throw. The runner on third read the sharp grounder and correctly held. The double play ended the threat and kept the deficit at one run.",
    teamworkTakeaway:"A bases-loaded double play is the highest-leverage defensive play in baseball — a 1.48-run swing in RE24. It requires the pitcher to induce a ground ball, the catcher to set the target, the shortstop to execute clean footwork, and the baserunner to resist the instinct to run on contact.",
    questions:[
      {pos:"pitcher",id:"sr1a3a",conceptTag:"pitch-sequencing",title:"Pitcher: Pitch for the DP",diff:3,cat:"pitcher",ageMin:12,ageMax:99,
        options:["Throw a two-seam sinker low-and-away to induce a ground ball to the pull side","Elevate a four-seam fastball to get a swing-and-miss strikeout","Throw a changeup low to get a weak grounder or a chase","Backdoor slider to freeze the hitter and steal strike three"],
        best:0,explanations:["With bases loaded, one out, and a 1-2 count, your priority is the ground-ball double play. A two-seam sinker low-and-away maximizes ground ball probability. The 1-2 count gives you an edge — the batting average at 1-2 is just .180, so the hitter is defensive. Even a weak grounder gets the force at home. RE24 with R123/1 out is 1.59; after a DP (bases empty, 2 outs) it drops to 0.11. That's a 1.48-run swing on one pitch.","Elevating for the strikeout is tempting at 1-2, but the risk-reward is wrong here. A missed high fastball is ball two (2-2, you lose count leverage), and if the hitter connects on an elevated pitch, the launch angle produces a fly ball — which scores the runner from third on a sac fly. Ground balls are the priority.","A changeup is a viable secondary option for inducing weak contact, but it's a slower pitch that's easier to put in play, because if the hitter sits on the changeup (which advanced hitters do at 1-2), he can drive it. The sinker's velocity and movement make it harder to barrel.","A backdoor slider for strike three sounds great on paper, but execution risk is high, since if it catches too much plate, the hitter can drive it. If it misses, it's 2-2 and you've lost the count edge. With a DP available, the high-percentage play is the ground ball inducer."],
        rates:[80,20,50,25],concept:"At 1-2 with bases loaded and one out, the sinker low-and-away is the highest-leverage pitch. It maximizes DP probability with a potential 1.48-run RE24 swing.",anim:"doubleplay"},
      {pos:"catcher",id:"sr1a3b",conceptTag:"dp-positioning",title:"Catcher: Frame the Strategy",diff:3,cat:"catcher",ageMin:12,ageMax:99,
        options:["Set up low-and-away with DP depth signaled — target the 6-4-3 or 1-2-3 paths","Set up high-and-tight to jam the hitter for a popup or whiff","Set up middle-in with a slider sign — force weak contact to the pull side","Call a pitchout to check the runner at third for a squeeze"],
        best:0,explanations:["This is elite game-calling. At 1-2 with the DP available, you set the target low-and-away because sinkers/two-seamers to that location generate ground balls at the highest rate. You've already signaled DP depth to the infield. A grounder to short gives you the 6-4-3; to second gives you the 4-6-3; to the pitcher gives you the 1-2-3 or 1-6-3. The batting average at 1-2 is .180 — the pitcher has a massive advantage. Your target maximizes that edge.","High-and-tight pitches at 1-2 with bases loaded carry significant risk. A hit-by-pitch forces in the tying run. A fly ball to the outfield scores a run on a sac fly. The DP is worth more than a strikeout here because it gets two outs and clears the bases.","Middle-in with a slider can work but is the second-best option. Sliders middle-in can be pulled hard — a line drive with bases loaded scores multiple runs. The sinker low-and-away has a higher ground ball probability with less damage potential on contact.","A pitchout with bases loaded wastes a pitch for no reason. The runners aren't going anywhere — every base is occupied. You'd be falling behind 2-2 and losing the 1-2 count advantage for nothing."],
        rates:[80,15,50,5],concept:"At 1-2 with the DP in order, set up low-and-away for the ground ball. The catcher's target selection determines whether the pitch induces the right contact type.",anim:"doubleplay"},
      {pos:"shortstop",id:"sr1a3c",conceptTag:"dp-positioning",title:"Shortstop: DP Pivot Mechanics",diff:3,cat:"fielder",ageMin:12,ageMax:99,
        options:["Cheat two steps toward second for DP depth, ready for the 6-4-3 pivot","Play at normal depth — range is more important than DP positioning","Move to double-play depth but shade toward the hole at third","Stay deep and concede the double play — just get the lead runner"],
        best:0,explanations:["Per DP_POSITIONING_MAP, with bases loaded and one out you should be at double-play depth — two steps closer to second base and one step shallower than normal. This positions you for the 6-4-3 pivot: field the grounder, chest-to-chest feed to the second baseman at the bag, and he turns the relay to first. Your footwork is critical: field, right foot plant, underhand or backhand feed to the pivot man's chest. The DP is the priority play here.","Normal depth prioritizes range over the double play. With bases loaded and one out, the DP is worth 1.48 runs in RE24 — far more valuable than the extra range. Even a slow roller that you field at DP depth still gets the force at home.","Shading toward the hole at third takes you farther from the pivot point at second base. The DP requires quick feet to second — every step farther from the bag adds time to the turn. Per DP_POSITIONING_MAP, shade toward second, not away from it.","Conceding the DP and playing deep for range is the wrong calculus. Getting one out leaves runners on with one more out needed. Getting two outs clears the bases. The mathematical value of the DP is overwhelming at 1.48 RE24."],
        rates:[80,20,25,15],concept:"Per DP_POSITIONING_MAP, bases loaded with one out requires double-play depth. The 6-4-3 pivot — a 1.48-run swing in RE24 — is the highest-value defensive play available.",anim:"doubleplay"},
      {pos:"baserunner",id:"sr1a3d",conceptTag:"baserunning-rates",title:"Runner on Third: Contact Quality Read",diff:3,cat:"baserunner",ageMin:12,ageMax:99,
        options:["Break on contact — any ground ball scores the tying run","Read the contact quality: go on slow rollers or balls hit to the right side, hold on sharp grounders near the battery","Tag up on all fly balls — even medium-depth flies can score the tying run","Hold at third and only score on a clean base hit or passed ball"],
        best:1,explanations:["Breaking on all contact with one out is a fundamentals error. A sharp grounder to the pitcher or a comebacker results in a 1-2-3 double play with you as the third out at home. With bases loaded and one out, the defense WANTS you to run into an out at home — it turns a potential DP into a triple play or at minimum gets the lead runner. Read the ball off the bat.","This is the correct read framework. Runners score from third on ground balls to the right side (1B/2B area) at approximately 88% because the fielder's momentum and throw angle point away from home. On slow rollers, the fielder must charge and throw, giving you time. But on sharp grounders to the pitcher, catcher, or third baseman, the throw home is short and direct — you're dead. Contact quality and direction determine everything.","Tagging on fly balls with bases loaded and one out is viable on deep flies, but medium-depth flies will get you thrown out. A sac fly here ties the game, which is valuable, but only if the fly is genuinely deep enough. The risk is getting thrown out at home for the second out while still having runners at first and second.","Holding at third only on base hits is too passive. With bases loaded and one out, ground balls to the right side, slow rollers, wild pitches, passed balls, and deep fly balls all create scoring opportunities. You need an active read, not a passive wait."],
        rates:[20,80,50,15],concept:"With R3 and one out, the read framework is: go on ground balls hit away from home (right side, slow rollers), hold on sharp grounders near the battery. Contact quality determines the decision.",anim:"score"}
    ]},
  {id:"sr2a3",title:"Steal Attempt at Second (All-Star)",emoji:"💨",color:"#06b6d4",diff:3,
    situation:{inning:"Top 4",outs:0,count:"1-1",runners:[1],score:[2,2]},
    desc:"Tied game, runner on first with speed. The steal window math — delivery time + pop time vs. runner time — determines everything. Four positions, one play, 3.5 seconds.",
    debrief:"The pitcher's slide step delivery was 1.25 seconds (vs. 1.5 in the full windup). The catcher's pop time was 1.95 seconds — total defense time of 3.20 seconds. The runner's time to second was 3.35 seconds, making him out by 0.15 seconds. The shortstop timed his break perfectly, arriving at the bag with the throw and applying a sweep tag on the front corner. The second baseman recognized the hole he'd leave and shaded toward the middle to compensate. Every tenth of a second mattered.",
    teamworkTakeaway:"Steal defense is pure math: pitcher delivery (1.2-1.5s) + catcher pop time (1.85-2.1s) must be less than the runner's time to second (3.2-3.6s). The slide step, quick transfer, and timed break are all links in the chain. The second baseman's awareness of the defensive hole completes the picture.",
    questions:[
      {pos:"pitcher",id:"sr2a3a",conceptTag:"steal-window",title:"Pitcher: Delivery Time Management",diff:3,cat:"pitcher",ageMin:12,ageMax:99,
        options:["Slide step to minimize delivery time while maintaining pitch quality","Vary your hold times between 1-3 seconds to disrupt the runner's timing, then slide step","Quick-pitch from the stretch before the runner gets his secondary lead","Step off and try a pickoff throw to first base"],
        best:1,explanations:["A straight slide step every time becomes predictable. The runner times your delivery and gets a consistent jump. While the slide step cuts delivery from ~1.5s to ~1.2s, if the runner knows it's coming, his jump improves by a comparable margin. Varying the hold time is what actually disrupts timing.","This is the complete approach. Per PICKOFF_MAP, varying hold times (1.0s, 1.5s, 2.5s) prevents the runner from timing your first movement. When you DO deliver, the slide step keeps the time to ~1.25s. Combined with the catcher's 1.95s pop time, total defense time is ~3.20s. The average runner needs 3.3-3.5s. Disruption + speed = out. The steal break-even at 0 outs is 72%, so you want to push the runner's success rate below that threshold.","Quick-pitching can draw a balk call if the batter isn't reasonably set. It's also difficult to locate when rushing, which means a hittable pitch. At 1-1, you don't want to fall behind 2-1 or throw a meatball.","Stepping off has value earlier in the sequence (establishing the threat), but once the runner is going, your job is to deliver quickly. A pickoff attempt after the runner has committed to stealing wastes time and accomplishes nothing — by the time you throw to first, he's already at second."],
        rates:[50,80,15,25],concept:"Steal prevention isn't just the slide step — it's hold-time variation that disrupts the runner's jump timing. Vary between 1-3 seconds, then deliver with a slide step for a total defense time of ~3.2s.",anim:"steal"},
      {pos:"catcher",id:"sr2a3b",conceptTag:"steal-window",title:"Catcher: Pop Time Optimization",diff:3,cat:"catcher",ageMin:12,ageMax:99,
        options:["Quick transfer from the crouch position, throw to the shortstop side of the bag on a line","Receive, rise slightly to generate momentum, and throw over the top for maximum velocity","Catch, crow-hop for accuracy, and throw to the center of the bag","Pre-position your feet toward second before the pitch to cheat on the throw"],
        best:0,explanations:["Pop time (catch to ball arriving at 2B) separates elite catchers from average ones. Elite MLB catchers post 1.85s; average is 2.0s. The quick transfer — glove to bare hand without a wasted movement — is the single biggest factor. Throw to the shortstop side because, per standard coverage, the SS covers on steals with RHBs. A low, line-drive throw (not rainbow) reaches the tag point fastest. At 1.95s pop time + 1.25s delivery, total defense time is 3.20s vs. runner's 3.3-3.5s.","Rising up adds time to the pop sequence. Every inch you rise is milliseconds added. The throw should come from a slight rise at most — not a full stand-up. Over-the-top release adds accuracy but at the cost of 0.1-0.15s, which is the margin between safe and out.","A crow-hop is for outfield throws, not catcher throws. The distance from home to second (~127 feet) doesn't require a crow-hop — arm strength from the crouch position is sufficient. The crow-hop adds 0.2-0.3s, which guarantees a safe call.","Pre-positioning your feet before the pitch telegraphs the play and takes you out of proper receiving position. If the pitch is a breaking ball in the dirt, you can't block it while your feet are cheating toward second. A passed ball with a runner on first is worse than a stolen base."],
        rates:[80,50,20,15],concept:"Pop time is the catcher's most critical metric on steals. Elite: 1.85s. Average: 2.0s. The quick transfer from crouch to throw — no wasted movements — is the difference-maker.",anim:"steal"},
      {pos:"shortstop",id:"sr2a3c",conceptTag:"steal-window",title:"Shortstop: Timed Break and Tag",diff:3,cat:"fielder",ageMin:12,ageMax:99,
        options:["Break toward second as the pitcher delivers, straddle the front edge, sweep tag low","Cheat to the bag before the pitch to guarantee you're there first","Break late (after the ball is caught by the catcher) to avoid leaving a hole","Signal the second baseman to cover instead so you can hold your range position"],
        best:0,explanations:["The timed break is the critical skill. Per standard steal coverage, with a RHB up, the shortstop covers second. You break toward the bag as the pitcher starts his delivery — your momentum carries you to the front corner of the bag. Straddle the front edge (not the back) so the tag sweeps across the runner's path. A low sweep tag on the runner's hand or foot, not a high tag that the runner slides under. Arrive with the throw, not before it and not after.","Cheating to the bag pre-pitch creates a hole in the 5-6 area that the hitter can exploit. A ground ball through the left side with the SS out of position is a guaranteed base hit. The timed break balances coverage responsibility with steal defense.","Breaking after the catcher catches it is 0.3-0.5s too late. At that point, the runner is 60% of the way to the bag. You need to arrive simultaneously with the throw — that requires reading the pitch delivery, not the catch.","Having the second baseman cover reverses the standard assignment and creates confusion. Per standard coverage protocols, the SS covers with a RHB and the 2B covers with a LHB. Switching creates miscommunication risk."],
        rates:[80,20,15,25],concept:"The SS timed break on a steal: start moving as the pitcher delivers, straddle the front edge of the bag, and apply a low sweep tag. Arrive with the throw, not before or after.",anim:"steal"},
      {pos:"secondBase",id:"sr2a3d",conceptTag:"steal-window",title:"Second Base: Coverage Awareness",diff:3,cat:"fielder",ageMin:12,ageMax:99,
        options:["Shade toward first base to cover the hole the SS leaves when he breaks to second","Hold your normal position — the steal isn't your problem, it's the SS's","Cheat toward second to back up the throw in case it gets past the shortstop","Break to second yourself and let the SS hold his position for range"],
        best:0,explanations:["Per standard steal coverage with a RHB up, the shortstop covers second base. That leaves a hole in the 5-6 area. Your job is defensive awareness: shade a step or two toward the middle to close the gap left by the SS's break. If the batter puts the ball in play to the left side, you need to be in range to field it. This is the hidden skill of steal defense — the off-ball fielder compensating for the coverage fielder's movement.","Ignoring the steal creates an exploitable defensive hole. Smart opposing coaches will call hit-and-runs specifically because they know the SS will break to cover second, leaving the left side exposed. Your awareness and shade are what prevent this.","Backing up the throw at second means TWO middle infielders abandon their fielding positions. If the batter hits the ball, there's no one covering the middle of the diamond. Backup at second is the center fielder's responsibility.","You covering second instead of the SS reverses the standard assignment with a RHB. The SS is on the glove side of second base for a RHB steal — better tag angle and shorter path. Switching creates confusion and a worse tag angle."],
        rates:[80,20,25,15],concept:"On a steal with a RHB, the SS covers second. The 2B's job is awareness: shade to cover the hole the SS leaves. It's the hidden skill of steal defense.",anim:"steal"}
    ]},
  {id:"sr3a3",title:"Sacrifice Bunt Situation (All-Star)",emoji:"🎯",color:"#22c55e",diff:3,
    situation:{inning:"Bot 7",outs:0,count:"0-0",runners:[1],score:[3,3]},
    desc:"Tie game, bottom 7th, runner on first, nobody out. Bunt defense vs. bunt execution — five positions, five coordinated roles. The RE24 cost of a sacrifice bunt is -0.23 runs, but win probability may justify it.",
    debrief:"Per BUNT_DEFENSE_MAP, the corners charged, the second baseman rotated to cover first, and the shortstop held near second for the force option. The pitcher threw a high fastball — the optimal anti-bunt pitch. The batter executed correctly: squared late, bunted softly down the first-base line away from the charging third baseman. RE24 dropped from 0.94 (R1, 0 out) to 0.69 (R2, 1 out) — a -0.25 run cost. But with the game tied in the 7th, moving the runner to scoring position raises win probability from 53% to 57%.",
    teamworkTakeaway:"Bunt defense is choreography from the BUNT_DEFENSE_MAP: pitcher makes the bunt difficult (high fastball), corners charge, 2B covers first, SS holds for the force. The offense pays a -0.23 RE24 cost for a +4% win probability gain in a tie game late.",
    questions:[
      {pos:"pitcher",id:"sr3a3a",conceptTag:"bunt-defense",title:"Pitcher: Anti-Bunt Arsenal",diff:3,cat:"pitcher",ageMin:12,ageMax:99,
        options:["High fastball up in the zone — hardest pitch to bunt down on the ground","Low sinker to induce a bunt into the ground for an easy fielding play","High inside fastball to jam the bat angle and force a popup","Slider low and away to get a bunt attempt that rolls foul"],
        best:0,explanations:["Per BUNT_DEFENSE_MAP, the pitcher's primary weapon against the bunt is the elevated fastball. High pitches are geometrically difficult to bunt on the ground — the bat angle required to redirect a pitch above the belt toward the ground almost guarantees a popup, foul ball, or missed bunt. Data shows bunt attempts on pitches in the upper third of the zone result in popup/foul rates significantly higher than low pitches. At 0-0, you have the luxury of throwing this pitch without count consequences.","A low sinker is counterproductive against a bunt, because the batter can angle the bat down naturally on a low pitch, making it easier to deaden the ball on the ground. You're essentially making the bunt easier for the hitter.","High inside is a viable second option, but HBP risk is real — a hit batter puts two runners on with nobody out — much worse than the bunt scenario. The high fastball over the plate or slightly away carries no HBP risk while being equally effective against the bunt.","A slider low and away that rolls foul is ball one if the batter doesn't chase, putting you at 1-0. At 0-0 you have a free pitch — use it on the high fastball that has a higher probability of getting a popup or whiff than a breaking ball that might land for a ball."],
        rates:[80,15,50,20],concept:"The elevated fastball is the optimal anti-bunt pitch. The bat angle required to bunt a high pitch onto the ground is geometrically unfavorable, maximizing popup and foul ball probability.",anim:"bunt"},
      {pos:"thirdBase",id:"sr3a3b",conceptTag:"bunt-defense",title:"Third Base: The Aggressive Charge",diff:3,cat:"fielder",ageMin:12,ageMax:99,
        options:["Charge hard as the pitcher delivers — field the bunt early for a possible force at second","Charge halfway and read whether the bunt is toward you or the pitcher","Stay back at third to prevent a slash hit through the vacated hole","Charge hard but angle toward the first-base line where most bunts go"],
        best:0,explanations:["Per BUNT_DEFENSE_MAP, the third baseman's assignment is an aggressive charge — full sprint toward home plate as the pitcher delivers. If you field the bunt early (within 40-50 feet of home), you have a throw to second base to get the lead runner. Even if you can't get the lead runner, fielding it quickly gives you the sure out at first. The key is committing fully — half-charges let the bunt die in no-man's-land.","A halfway charge is the worst of both worlds. You're not close enough to field the bunt quickly for the force at second, and you're not back far enough to field your position. Per BUNT_DEFENSE_MAP, the third baseman must commit to the full charge. Hesitation creates dead zones in the defense.","Protecting against the slash hit is the shortstop's secondary responsibility, not yours. If the batter pulls back and swings, the SS shifts to cover third. Your primary assignment is the charge — trust the system.","Angling toward the first-base line takes you away from the most direct path to the ball. The batter can bunt to either side. Your charge should be straight toward home plate, then adjust to where the bunt goes once it's down."],
        rates:[80,25,15,20],concept:"Per BUNT_DEFENSE_MAP, the 3B charges aggressively on a sac bunt. A full sprint gives you the chance to get the force at second — the highest-value outcome.",anim:"bunt"},
      {pos:"firstBase",id:"sr3a3c",conceptTag:"bunt-defense",title:"First Base: Charge and Cover",diff:3,cat:"fielder",ageMin:12,ageMax:99,
        options:["Charge in aggressively to field any bunt to the right side","Hold at first to keep the runner from taking a big lead, then react","Charge hard, but if someone else fields the bunt, sprint back to cover first for the throw","Charge halfway and read the bunt direction"],
        best:2,explanations:["Charging in without a plan to cover first means nobody is there for the throw. Per BUNT_DEFENSE_MAP, the second baseman rotates to cover first when the first baseman charges, but this requires coordination. Your charge should include awareness of whether you or the pitcher/3B will field the bunt.","Holding the runner at first is irrelevant during a sacrifice bunt — the runner is going to second regardless. Your priority per the BUNT_DEFENSE_MAP is participating in the bunt defense, not holding a runner who's already been given the green light to advance.","This is the complete play. Per BUNT_DEFENSE_MAP, the first baseman charges aggressively to field bunts to the right side. If the third baseman or pitcher fields the bunt, you immediately redirect to cover first base for the throw. The second baseman is also rotating to first, but you're the primary coverage. This dual-responsibility approach is what makes bunt defense work.","A halfway charge is hesitation. In bunt defense, you need to commit. The bunt is only on the ground for 1-2 seconds before someone fields it. Halfway gets you to neither the ball nor the bag in time."],
        rates:[25,15,80,20],concept:"Per BUNT_DEFENSE_MAP, the 1B charges but maintains first-base coverage awareness. If someone else fields it, redirect to first for the throw — the dual-responsibility play.",anim:"bunt"},
      {pos:"secondBase",id:"sr3a3e",conceptTag:"bunt-defense",title:"Second Base: Cover First",diff:3,cat:"fielder",ageMin:12,ageMax:99,
        options:["Rotate toward first base to cover when the first baseman charges in","Hold your position near second base for a possible force play on the bunt","Charge in to help field the bunt — more defenders near the ball is better","Cover the area between first and second in case of a slash hit"],
        best:0,explanations:["Per BUNT_DEFENSE_MAP, when the first baseman charges on a bunt play, the second baseman rotates to cover first base. This is a predetermined assignment — you start rotating as soon as the bunt is shown. Your path is a curved route to the inside (home plate side) of first base so you can receive the throw while touching the bag. This rotation is what allows the first baseman to charge aggressively.","Holding near second for the force play sounds logical, but the shortstop handles force play coverage at second per the BUNT_DEFENSE_MAP. If you stay at second, nobody covers first and the batter reaches safely even on a well-fielded bunt.","Three fielders charging the bunt creates chaos, not efficiency. Bunt defense is about coverage assignments. If you charge in, nobody covers first, and the entire play breaks down even if someone fields the bunt cleanly.","The slash hit is a secondary concern covered by defensive positioning. Your primary assignment is first base coverage. If the batter pulls back and swings, the SS covers third and you return to your normal position. Don't abandon the primary assignment for a contingency."],
        rates:[80,20,15,25],concept:"Per BUNT_DEFENSE_MAP, the 2B rotates to cover first base when the 1B charges on a bunt. This predetermined rotation is what makes aggressive bunt defense possible.",anim:"bunt"},
      {pos:"batter",id:"sr3a3d",conceptTag:"bunt-re24",title:"Batter: Bunt Placement Tactics",diff:3,cat:"batter",ageMin:12,ageMax:99,
        options:["Bunt hard toward third to try to beat the throw and reach base safely","Square late and bunt softly down the first-base line, away from the charging third baseman","Push bunt past the pitcher toward the second baseman's vacated area","Show bunt early to freeze the corners, then pull back and slash"],
        best:1,explanations:["Bunting hard toward the charging third baseman is the worst placement. He's already sprinting toward you — a hard bunt goes directly to him and he has a throw to second for the force on the lead runner. Even if you beat it out, the lead runner might be forced. Soft and away from the charge is the principle.","Textbook sacrifice bunt execution. Square late (as the pitcher commits to home) to minimize the defense's reaction time. Bunt softly down the first-base line because the third baseman is charging from the opposite side — maximum distance from the nearest fielder. A sacrifice bunt costs about -0.23 expected runs vs. swinging away (RE24: R1/0 out = 0.94, R2/1 out = 0.69). But in a tie game in the 7th, the win probability increase from moving the runner to scoring position (+4%) justifies the RE24 cost.","A push bunt to the vacated second base area is theoretically clever but extremely difficult to execute consistently. The bat angle and force required to place the ball in that specific zone makes it a low-percentage play. A mishit goes right back to the pitcher.","Showing bunt and slashing goes against the team's strategy. The coach called a bunt — the entire offensive plan depends on moving the runner. A slash hit also risks a line drive that the infield catches for a double play, losing the runner on first."],
        rates:[15,80,25,20],concept:"The sacrifice bunt costs -0.23 RE24 but gains +4% win probability in a tie game late. Execution: square late, bunt softly away from the charge, accept the out to move the runner.",anim:"bunt"}
    ]},
  {id:"sr4a3",title:"Extra-Base Hit to the Gap (All-Star)",emoji:"🏃",color:"#f97316",diff:3,
    situation:{inning:"Top 5",outs:1,count:"0-0",runners:[1],score:[1,2]},
    desc:"A drive to left-center splits the outfielders. Per CUTOFF_RELAY_MAP, the SS is lead relay, 2B is trail, and the pitcher has a backup assignment. Five positions must execute within 4 seconds.",
    debrief:"Per CUTOFF_RELAY_MAP, the SS sprinted to the relay position ~150 feet from home, arms up, aligned between the CF and home plate. The 2B positioned as trail man, 20 feet behind and 10 feet offset, ready to redirect to third if needed. The CF fielded cleanly, set feet, and hit the SS in the chest. The pitcher sprinted to back up home plate per BACKUP_MAP. The runner rounded third hard, read the relay throw coming in strong and on-line, and held. Five positions, one system, executed in 3.8 seconds.",
    teamworkTakeaway:"Per CUTOFF_RELAY_MAP: on left-side hits (LF line, LF-CF gap), the SS is lead relay and the 2B is trail man. The pitcher backs up home per BACKUP_MAP. The relay system turns a 300+ foot throw into two accurate 150-foot throws — faster and more reliable.",
    questions:[
      {pos:"centerField",id:"sr4a3a",conceptTag:"relay-double-cut",title:"CF: Relay Throw Execution",diff:3,cat:"fielder",ageMin:12,ageMax:99,
        options:["Field the ball, set your feet, and throw a strong one-hopper to the relay man's chest","Field on the run and throw home in one motion — skip the relay man","Field and throw to the trail man behind the relay for a redirect to third","Hold the ball momentarily to read where the runners are before throwing"],
        best:0,explanations:["Per CUTOFF_RELAY_MAP, the outfielder's assignment on extra-base hits is to hit the relay man's chest with a strong one-hopper. A throw from deep left-center to home is 300+ feet — even elite arms lose accuracy at that distance, and a rainbow throw lets runners advance. The relay system breaks it into two ~150-foot throws that are faster and more accurate. Set your feet, aim for the relay man's chest, and throw through the target.","Skipping the relay from 300+ feet is a low-percentage play. The ball arrives late (rainbow trajectory), likely offline, and runners advance on the misplay. The relay system exists specifically because direct throws from the deep outfield are unreliable.","Throwing to the trail man instead of the lead relay disrupts the system, which means per CUTOFF_RELAY_MAP, the lead relay (SS on left-side hits) is your primary target. The trail man handles redirect decisions. Your job is to hit the lead relay.","Holding the ball in the outfield while reading runners is a cardinal sin, because every second you hold it, runners advance. The relay man makes the decision about which base to throw to — your job is to get the ball to him immediately."],
        rates:[80,15,25,5],concept:"On extra-base hits, the outfielder hits the relay man's chest with a one-hopper. The relay system converts one 300+ foot throw into two accurate 150-foot throws.",anim:"throwHome"},
      {pos:"shortstop",id:"sr4a3b",conceptTag:"relay-double-cut",title:"SS: Lead Relay Positioning",diff:3,cat:"fielder",ageMin:12,ageMax:99,
        options:["Sprint to a position ~150 feet from home, aligned between the outfielder and home plate, arms up","Position yourself between the outfielder and third base for the most likely throw","Stay near second base to cover in case the batter tries to advance","Sprint to the outfield to help the CF retrieve the ball"],
        best:0,explanations:["Per CUTOFF_RELAY_MAP, on balls hit to the left side (LF line, LF-CF gap, deep CF), the shortstop is the lead relay man. Position ~150 feet from home plate in a direct line between the outfielder and home. Arms up high and loud call so the outfielder can find you. After catching the relay, you decide: throw home if the runner is going, throw to third to cut off the batter, or hold. The trail man (2B) communicates 'home,' 'cut third,' or 'hold.'","Aligning between the outfielder and third gives up the throw home. Per CUTOFF_RELAY_MAP, the default alignment is always toward home plate. The trail man (2B) handles redirect calls if third is the right play. Your primary line is always outfielder-to-you-to-home.","Staying at second means no relay chain exists. A 300+ foot direct throw from the outfielder is unreliable. Without the lead relay, the defense essentially concedes extra bases. The 2B or another fielder can cover second.","Going to the outfield to help creates a hole in the relay chain. The CF can field the ball alone — your value is in the relay position, not in the outfield. Running out there means the ball has no relay target."],
        rates:[80,20,15,5],concept:"Per CUTOFF_RELAY_MAP, on left-side extra-base hits, the SS is the lead relay man. Position ~150 feet from home, aligned between outfielder and home, arms up.",anim:"throwHome"},
      {pos:"secondBase",id:"sr4a3c",conceptTag:"relay-double-cut",title:"2B: Trail Man Assignment",diff:3,cat:"fielder",ageMin:12,ageMax:99,
        options:["Position as trail man — 20 feet behind the SS relay, offset slightly, ready to redirect or communicate","Cover second base in case the batter rounds first too aggressively","Line up as a second relay man directly behind the shortstop for a double cut","Charge into short right field to back up the center fielder's throw to the SS"],
        best:0,explanations:["Per CUTOFF_RELAY_MAP, the trail man positions 20 feet behind the lead relay and 10 feet offset so you have a clear view of home and third. Your jobs: (1) communicate to the lead relay where to throw ('home!' or 'cut, three!' or 'hold!'), (2) if the relay throw from the outfielder is offline and goes over the SS's head, you're the backup to catch it and redirect. The trail man is the relay system's insurance and intelligence.","Covering second base is a lower priority than the trail assignment. With the batter at first or second on an extra-base hit, the play is at third or home. A ball at second base has no force play value. The SS can cover second after the play if needed.","A double-cut (two relay men in direct line) is used for very deep hits — balls to the wall or over the wall (relay throws from near the fence). On a standard gap hit, the single relay with a trail man is the correct formation.","Backing up the throw to the SS from the right-field side puts you in the outfield where you can't see the play develop. The trail position behind the relay gives you the best view and the ability to communicate baserunner locations."],
        rates:[80,25,20,15],concept:"Per CUTOFF_RELAY_MAP, the 2B is trail man on left-side relay throws — positioned behind the SS, communicating redirect calls ('home,' 'cut three,' 'hold') and backing up offline throws.",anim:"throwHome"},
      {pos:"pitcher",id:"sr4a3d",conceptTag:"backup-duties",title:"Pitcher: Backup Assignment",diff:3,cat:"pitcher",ageMin:12,ageMax:99,
        options:["Sprint to back up home plate, positioning behind the catcher in line with the relay throw","Stay on the mound and cover the area between home and the pitcher's mound","Run to back up third base in case the throw from the relay goes to third","Cover first base in case the batter tries to advance on the throw home"],
        best:0,explanations:["Per BACKUP_MAP, on extra-base hits with a potential play at home, the pitcher's assignment is to sprint to back up home plate. Position yourself behind the catcher, ~20-30 feet up the backstop line, in line with the incoming relay throw. If the throw gets past the catcher, you're there to prevent additional bases. This is a sprint — you have 3-4 seconds from contact to get there.","Staying on the mound leaves no backup behind home plate. If the relay throw gets past the catcher, the ball rolls to the backstop and every runner advances an additional base. Per BACKUP_MAP, the pitcher NEVER stays on the mound during an extra-base hit.","Backing up third base is the left fielder's assignment per BACKUP_MAP, not the pitcher's. The pitcher's backup is always home plate on potential scoring plays. Each position has a specific backup assignment to avoid redundancy.","Covering first base on an extra-base hit is unnecessary — the batter is already past first and heading to second or third. First base coverage is a non-play. Your value is behind home plate where the relay throw is heading."],
        rates:[80,10,25,15],concept:"Per BACKUP_MAP, the pitcher backs up home plate on extra-base hits with potential plays at home. Sprint behind the catcher, ~20-30 feet back, in line with the relay.",anim:"throwHome"},
      {pos:"baserunner",id:"sr4a3e",conceptTag:"baserunning-rates",title:"Runner on First: Aggression Calculus",diff:3,cat:"baserunner",ageMin:12,ageMax:99,
        options:["Sprint home from first — a ball in the gap should score you easily","Round third hard, read the relay throw quality, and commit or hold based on the throw","Stop at third automatically — don't risk the out at home with one out and your team trailing","Stop at second — take the sure extra base and avoid any risk"],
        best:1,explanations:["Blindly sprinting home from first on every gap hit gets you thrown out on clean relay executions. A well-executed relay (CF to SS to catcher) takes about 3.5-4 seconds. Your first-to-home time is about 12-13 seconds. If the relay is clean and on-line, you're out. If it's offline, you score. The read determines the outcome.","This is the optimal approach. Runners advance from first to third on approximately 28% of singles, but on extra-base hits to the gap, third is nearly automatic. The decision point is home. Round third aggressively (force the defense to make a perfect relay), then read: if the relay throw is offline, bounced, or cut to the wrong base, score. If it's on-line and strong, hold at third. You're now 90 feet from scoring with one out — a productive outcome. This is smart aggression: pressure the defense and capitalize on mistakes.","Automatic stops are never optimal. The situation (trailing by one, one out) demands aggression. A runner at third with one out scores on sac flies, grounders to the right side, wild pitches, and passed balls. But a runner who scores ties the game immediately. The read framework maximizes value: you get the run when the defense falters, and you hold safely when they execute.","Stopping at second on a ball in the gap is extremely conservative. Third base is nearly automatic on any gap hit with a running start from first. You'd be leaving 90 feet of advancement — and all the scoring opportunities from third — on the table."],
        rates:[20,80,25,10],concept:"On gap hits from first, third base is automatic. The decision is whether to score: round third hard, read the relay quality, and commit only when the throw is offline or mishandled.",anim:"score"}
    ]},
  {id:"sr5a3",title:"Full Count Showdown (All-Star)",emoji:"⚡",color:"#a855f7",diff:3,
    situation:{inning:"Bot 8",outs:2,count:"3-2",runners:[2],score:[5,5]},
    desc:"Tie game, Bot 8th, two outs, runner on second, full count. At 3-2, the BA is .230 and the OBP is .350. The runner goes on the pitch. Win probability hinges on this at-bat.",
    debrief:"At 3-2, the count is nearly neutral (BA .230, OBP .350). The pitcher threw his best fastball on the corner — conviction over deception. The batter protected the plate with a two-strike approach: fouled off a tough slider, then lined the next pitch to right. The runner was going on the pitch (zero risk with two outs — ball four advances him, strikeout ends the inning regardless), scoring easily with a head start. The shortstop had shaded toward third for the possible grounder, not shading toward the hole, because with R2 and 2 outs, a ground ball through the hole doesn't matter if they get the force.",
    teamworkTakeaway:"In high-leverage full-count situations: the pitcher trusts his best pitch (conviction > deception), the batter protects the plate (don't let the umpire decide), the manager sends the runner (zero-risk free play), and the shortstop adjusts positioning for the game situation (R2/2 outs = no hole concern).",
    questions:[
      {pos:"pitcher",id:"sr5a3a",conceptTag:"count-leverage",title:"Pitcher: The 3-2 Decision Tree",diff:3,cat:"pitcher",ageMin:12,ageMax:99,
        options:["Fastball on the corner with conviction — your best pitch in the highest-leverage spot","Secondary pitch (slider/change) to get the batter to chase out of the zone","Intentional walk to set up a force at every base with the next hitter","Fastball elevated for the swing-and-miss strikeout"],
        best:0,explanations:["At 3-2 with two outs in a tie game, this is the highest-leverage pitch of the game. The data says: 3-2 count batting average is .230 with an OBP of .350. The count is essentially neutral. Your best pitch with conviction gives you the highest probability of a quality outcome. A well-located fastball on the black has margin — if you miss by an inch, it's still borderline. A secondary pitch that misses is ball four. Compete with your best offering.","Secondary pitches at 3-2 carry higher walk risk. A slider needs precise location — if it catches too much plate at 3-2, the hitter is sitting on it and drives it. If it misses, it's ball four. At 3-2 with two outs, the walk puts the tying run at second AND the winning run at first. The risk-reward favors the fastball.","An intentional walk puts the winning run on base. With two outs, the force play doesn't help — you still need to get the next hitter out. And now a single scores two runs instead of one. Never put the winning run on base in a tie game unless there's a massive platoon advantage and an open base creates a force.","Elevated fastball for the whiff is higher risk than corner location. An elevated fastball that doesn't get a swing is ball four. The corner fastball has a bigger margin: called strike, foul ball, or weak contact are all acceptable outcomes. Elevation is high-variance; location is high-floor."],
        rates:[80,50,10,25],concept:"At 3-2 with the game on the line, throw your best pitch with conviction. The corner fastball has the highest floor: called strike, foul, or weak contact are all acceptable outcomes.",anim:"strike"},
      {pos:"batter",id:"sr5a3b",conceptTag:"count-leverage",title:"Batter: Two-Strike Approach",diff:3,cat:"batter",ageMin:12,ageMax:99,
        options:["Sit on fastball and ambush — he's going to challenge you with his best","Protect the plate: shorten up, fight off tough pitches, put hittable ones in play","Guess location (inside) and look to pull for extra bases","Take the pitch and hope for ball four — a walk ties the runner at third"],
        best:1,explanations:["Sitting fastball at 3-2 with two outs is a gamble. If the pitcher throws a quality secondary pitch, you're frozen for strike three. At 3-2, the OBP is .350 (walk rate ~12%) and the BA is .230. The plate-protection approach covers both outcomes: you can get a hit (.230) OR draw the walk (.120 walk rate). Guessing one pitch eliminates the walk as an outcome.","This is the textbook two-strike approach. At 3-2 with two outs and the game on the line, shorten your swing, cover both sides of the plate, and fight off borderline pitches. The runner on second is going on the pitch — even a single scores him. You don't need a home run; you need the ball in play. Foul off tough pitches to extend the at-bat. Put hittable pitches in play. The OBP at 3-2 is .350 — you have a 35% chance of reaching base through any method. Protect the plate to maximize that number.","Guessing location eliminates your ability to cover the other side of the plate. If you sit inside and the pitch is away, you either take a called strike three or weakly foul it off. The two-strike approach is reactionary, not anticipatory.","Taking 3-2 with two outs and the game on the line lets the umpire decide the game. If the pitch is borderline (and it will be), a called strike three ends the inning. You never want the bat on your shoulder with two outs and the tying run on second."],
        rates:[25,80,15,10],concept:"At 3-2 with two outs, protect the plate: shorten up, fight off borderline pitches, put hittable ones in play. The OBP at 3-2 is .350 — protect the plate to maximize it.",anim:"hit"},
      {pos:"manager",id:"sr5a3c",conceptTag:"win-probability",title:"Manager: The Zero-Risk Send",diff:3,cat:"manager",ageMin:12,ageMax:99,
        options:["Send the runner on the pitch — it's a zero-risk free play with two outs and a full count","Hold the runner to avoid a caught stealing that ends the inning","Call a hit-and-run to guarantee the runner is moving on contact","Signal the batter to bunt the runner to third"],
        best:0,explanations:["With two outs and a full count, sending the runner is a pure zero-risk play. Three outcomes: (1) Ball four — runner advances to third automatically with the walk. (2) Strikeout — inning is over regardless of where the runner is. (3) Ball in play — the runner has a massive head start, easily scoring from second on any single. There is literally no scenario where the runner being in motion hurts you. This is one of the few true 'free plays' in baseball.","Holding the runner at second with two outs and a full count is leaving free value on the table. There is zero risk to sending him. If it's ball four, he's at third instead of second. On contact, he scores from second with a head start instead of having to read and react. The only 'risk' is a pitchout — but a pitchout at 3-2 is ball four and the runner goes to third anyway.","A hit-and-run at 3-2 with two outs is functionally identical to 'send the runner' since he should already be going. The difference is that a hit-and-run pressures the batter to swing at anything, including ball four. Just send the runner and let the batter make the right decision.","Bunting with two outs is an automatic out that ends the inning. This is never the play with two outs."],
        rates:[80,15,50,5],concept:"With two outs and a full count, sending the runner is a zero-risk play. Ball four = free advance. K = inning over anyway. Contact = head start to score. There is no downside.",anim:"steal"},
      {pos:"shortstop",id:"sr5a3d",conceptTag:"infield-positioning",title:"SS: Situational Positioning",diff:3,cat:"fielder",ageMin:12,ageMax:99,
        options:["Shade toward the middle (second base side) to cover the hole — a single through the middle wins the game","Shade toward third base side for the potential ground ball to your left — with two outs, the force at first is the only play","Play at standard depth and rely on your range to cover both sides","Cheat in for the potential slow roller to get the out at first on a close play"],
        best:1,explanations:["Shading toward the middle to 'protect the hole' is a common instinct, but it's wrong here. Per PRE_PITCH_POSITIONING_MAP, with R2 and 2 outs, a ground ball through the hole doesn't matter if you get the force at first. The runner scores on any base hit regardless of where it goes. Your job is to maximize the probability of getting the batter out at first, which means positioning for the highest-probability ground ball based on the hitter's tendencies.","With R2 and two outs, the defense only needs one more out. The force at first is the only play on a ground ball. Per PRE_PITCH_POSITIONING_MAP, your positioning should maximize the probability of fielding any ground ball and throwing the batter out. With a RHB up and a fastball on the corner expected, shade toward the third-base side where pulled ground balls go. A ball through the middle scores the runner regardless — what matters is catching the balls you can reach and converting the out at first.","Standard depth gives you range, but positioning isn't just about depth — lateral shade matters. With the count at 3-2 and a fastball likely, the pull-side ground ball is the most common outcome on contact. Standard positioning without considering the count and pitch type leaves value on the table.","Cheating in for the slow roller reduces your range on ground balls hit with authority. The most common ground ball at 3-2 is on a fastball — those are hit sharply, not slowly. Playing shallow costs you more ground balls than it gains."],
        rates:[25,80,20,15],concept:"Per PRE_PITCH_POSITIONING_MAP, with R2/2 outs, a hit through the hole scores the runner regardless. Position to maximize your probability of converting the out at first based on pitch type and hitter tendencies.",anim:"groundout"}
    ]},
  {id:"sr6a3",title:"Squeeze Play Alert (All-Star)",emoji:"🤫",color:"#eab308",diff:3,
    situation:{inning:"Bot 7",outs:1,count:"1-1",runners:[3],score:[2,3]},
    desc:"Runner on third, one out, down by one in the 7th. The squeeze is baseball's highest-commitment play — the runner commits before the pitch arrives. Per SQUEEZE_MAP, every defender has a recognition and response assignment.",
    debrief:"Per SQUEEZE_MAP, the squeeze requires total commitment from the offense and instant recognition from the defense. The batter squared late at the last possible moment — minimizing the defense's reaction window. The runner broke on the pitcher's first movement. The third baseman read the runner's aggressive lead but called 'SQUEEZE!' a fraction too late. The catcher recognized the batter squaring and set up to receive the bunt, but the ball was bunted softly down the first-base line — out of the catcher's range. Run scored. The pitcher's high-inside pitch was correct per SQUEEZE_MAP, but the batter got the bat on it. Execution beat recognition by 0.5 seconds.",
    teamworkTakeaway:"Per SQUEEZE_MAP: the batter squares late and bunts everything (any miss = runner is dead). The runner commits on the pitcher's first move (no read, pure commitment). The defense relies on recognition: 3B reads the runner's lead, catcher reads the square, pitcher throws high-inside. Recognition must beat execution — and execution has the advantage.",
    questions:[
      {pos:"batter",id:"sr6a3a",conceptTag:"squeeze-play",title:"Batter: Commitment and Execution",diff:3,cat:"batter",ageMin:12,ageMax:99,
        options:["Square early to get the best bat position for a clean bunt","Square at the last possible moment and bunt the ball regardless of location","Only bunt if the pitch is in the strike zone — don't bunt a bad pitch","Show bunt and read the pitch — pull back on a pitchout and try to protect the runner"],
        best:1,explanations:["Squaring early on a suicide squeeze is the cardinal sin. Per SQUEEZE_MAP, the defense reads the batter's square to trigger their response. If you show bunt while the pitcher can still adjust, he throws high-inside (impossible to bunt on the ground) or throws a pitchout. The runner is dead by 20+ feet. Late square = minimal reaction time for the defense.","Per SQUEEZE_MAP, the suicide squeeze requires total batter commitment. The runner breaks for home on the pitcher's first movement toward home — before the batter has even squared. If you don't bunt the ball, the catcher has it and the runner is out by 20 feet. You MUST get the bat on the ball regardless of pitch location. Square at the last possible moment (as the ball is halfway to the plate), angle the bat down, and deaden the ball on the ground. Any bunt on the ground scores the run — location is secondary to contact.","Taking a bad pitch on a squeeze play means the catcher has the ball and the runner is out. There is no pitch discrimination on a suicide squeeze — you bunt everything. The ball could be head-high or in the dirt. You foul it off at worst. But a missed bunt or taken pitch is a guaranteed out on the runner.","Pulling back on a pitchout leaves the runner stranded between third and home with no chance. The squeeze is a commitment play — once the runner breaks, the batter's job is contact. Per SQUEEZE_MAP, the batter's only job is to get the bat on the ball. Everything else is secondary."],
        rates:[15,80,20,25],concept:"Per SQUEEZE_MAP, the suicide squeeze is total commitment. Square at the last moment, bunt everything regardless of location. Any missed bunt = runner out by 20 feet.",anim:"bunt"},
      {pos:"pitcher",id:"sr6a3b",conceptTag:"squeeze-recognition",title:"Pitcher: In-Delivery Recognition",diff:3,cat:"pitcher",ageMin:12,ageMax:99,
        options:["If you recognize the squeeze during delivery, throw high-and-inside — impossible to bunt down","Throw your normal pitch and trust the fielders to make the play on the bunt","Step off the rubber to kill the play and prevent the runner from scoring","Throw a pitchout wide to give the catcher a clear throw to tag the runner"],
        best:0,explanations:["Per SQUEEZE_MAP, the pitcher's primary weapon against a recognized squeeze is the high-inside fastball. The bat angle required to bunt a pitch that's up and in toward the ground is geometrically almost impossible — the batter pops it up, fouls it off, or misses entirely. In all three cases, the runner is dead between third and home. Recognition cues: the runner at third takes an aggressively large lead, the runner breaks before or with your delivery, or the batter shows bunt motion. Even if you only recognize it halfway through your delivery, redirect toward high-inside.","Throwing a normal pitch when you recognize the squeeze is surrendering. A normal-location pitch is buntable, and any bunt on the ground with the runner already sprinting home scores the run. The squeeze is the offense's most aggressive play — you must match that aggression with the high-inside counter.","Stepping off the rubber only works if you recognize the squeeze before committing to your delivery. Once your arm is moving forward, you must throw to the plate (stepping off mid-delivery is a balk). The recognition window for stepping off is tiny — the high-inside pitch works regardless of when in the delivery you recognize it.","A pitchout can work but must be called before the pitch. In-the-moment recognition calls for the high-inside fastball, not a pitchout. A pitchout thrown reactively often ends up as a wild pitch because the catcher isn't set up for it."],
        rates:[80,10,50,25],concept:"Per SQUEEZE_MAP, throw high-and-inside when you recognize the squeeze. The bat angle required to bunt a high-inside pitch onto the ground is geometrically impossible.",anim:"bunt"},
      {pos:"thirdBase",id:"sr6a3c",conceptTag:"squeeze-recognition",title:"Third Base: The Early Warning",diff:3,cat:"fielder",ageMin:12,ageMax:99,
        options:["Watch the runner's lead at third — an aggressive break means squeeze, yell 'SQUEEZE!' immediately","Charge toward home as soon as you suspect a bunt to field it quickly","Stay back at your position to prevent a slash hit through the vacated left side","Ignore the runner and watch the batter's hands for the bunt show"],
        best:0,explanations:["Per SQUEEZE_MAP, the third baseman is the defense's early warning system. The runner gives away the squeeze before the batter does — he takes an unusually aggressive lead or breaks for home as the pitcher starts his delivery. Your voice is the trigger: 'SQUEEZE!' tells the pitcher to go high-inside and tells the catcher to prepare for the play at the plate. Recognition speed is everything — the earlier you call it, the more time the battery has to react.","Charging before confirming the squeeze leaves third base wide open. If the batter pulls back and swings (slash play), a ground ball to the left side is a free hit with nobody near third. Per SQUEEZE_MAP, confirm the squeeze first (read the runner), call it, THEN react to the bunt.","Staying back means no early warning for the pitcher. The third baseman has the best view of the runner's lead and break. Without your call, the pitcher may not recognize the squeeze until the batter squares — which is too late to adjust the pitch.","The runner's movement is a more reliable indicator than the batter's hands. A skilled squeeze batter squares at the last possible moment. But the runner must break early enough to score — his timing is the tell. Read the runner first, then confirm with the batter's hands."],
        rates:[80,20,15,25],concept:"Per SQUEEZE_MAP, the 3B is the early warning system. The runner's aggressive lead/break reveals the squeeze before the batter squares. Call 'SQUEEZE!' immediately to trigger the battery's response.",anim:"bunt"},
      {pos:"catcher",id:"sr6a3d",conceptTag:"squeeze-recognition",title:"Catcher: Plate Defense",diff:3,cat:"catcher",ageMin:12,ageMax:99,
        options:["If you recognize the squeeze, jump out front to field the bunt and tag the runner before he arrives","Receive the pitch normally, then react to the bunt if it's laid down","If the batter misses or pops up the bunt, immediately throw to third or tag the runner at home","Call a pitchout pre-pitch if you suspect a squeeze based on the runner's lead"],
        best:2,explanations:["Jumping out in front of the plate before the pitch is catcher's interference if you contact the batter. You also can't receive the pitch if you're in front of the plate. Your positioning must stay behind the plate until the ball is bunted or missed. The play happens after the pitch, not before it.","Receiving normally and reacting after is too passive when you've recognized the squeeze. Per SQUEEZE_MAP, if the pitcher throws high-inside on the squeeze recognition and the batter misses or pops up, the runner is stranded between third and home. Your job is to immediately apply the tag or throw to third. Read the pitch result and execute the tag.","Per SQUEEZE_MAP, the catcher's play on a failed squeeze is immediate: if the batter misses, pops up, or fouls off the pitch, the runner is committed and can't get back to third in time. Catch the ball and either tag the runner coming home or throw to third to catch him retreating. The key is recognizing the bunt attempt failed and reacting instantly. On a successful bunt (ball on the ground), field it and throw to first for the out — the run scores but you get the batter.","A pitchout can work if called before the pitch, but it requires anticipating the squeeze, not just recognizing it. Pre-pitch pitchout is a guess — if wrong, you've wasted a pitch and fallen behind 2-1. The high-inside pitch is more effective because it's still a competitive pitch that also defeats the squeeze."],
        rates:[15,25,80,50],concept:"Per SQUEEZE_MAP, if the squeeze bunt fails (miss, popup, foul), the catcher immediately tags the committed runner or throws to third. The runner can't retreat 90 feet in time.",anim:"bunt"}
    ]},
  {id:"sr7a3",title:"Rundown Chaos (All-Star)",emoji:"🔄",color:"#6366f1",diff:3,
    situation:{inning:"Top 3",outs:0,count:"0-0",runners:[1,3],score:[0,1]},
    desc:"Runners on first and third, nobody out. The runner on first is caught. Per RUNDOWN_MAP, the goal is one throw maximum. But the runner at third is watching. Per FIRST_THIRD_MAP, the defense must solve both problems simultaneously.",
    debrief:"Per RUNDOWN_MAP, the first baseman chased the runner toward second with the ball held high, running hard, creating the 'runway' that the shortstop shortened from the other side. Per FIRST_THIRD_MAP, the catcher watched the runner at third while the first baseman kept peripheral awareness. When R3 broke for home on the throw toward second, the first baseman redirected home instead. Tag applied. Per RUNDOWN_MAP, the ideal rundown is one throw maximum — this one took two (1B to home), which is acceptable because the runner at third forced the adjustment.",
    teamworkTakeaway:"Per RUNDOWN_MAP: chase toward the next base, get the out in one throw max. Per FIRST_THIRD_MAP: with R1+R3, the defense must solve the rundown while watching the trail runner. The catcher and first baseman split awareness — the catcher watches R3 while the first baseman executes the rundown.",
    questions:[
      {pos:"firstBase",id:"sr7a3a",conceptTag:"rundown-mechanics",title:"1B: Chase Mechanics and R3 Awareness",diff:3,cat:"fielder",ageMin:12,ageMax:99,
        options:["Chase toward second with ball held high, but redirect throw home if R3 breaks","Run the runner back to first and tag him yourself — safest play, no throw needed","Chase toward second making quick throws back and forth until you get the tag","Throw immediately to the SS at second and let the middle infielders handle the rundown"],
        best:0,explanations:["Per RUNDOWN_MAP and FIRST_THIRD_MAP combined, this is the dual-responsibility play. Chase the runner toward second (ball up, running hard) to shorten the distance for the receiving fielder. Per FIRST_THIRD_MAP, maintain peripheral awareness of the runner at third. The catcher is your partner in R3 surveillance — he communicates if R3 breaks. If R3 commits to home, redirect your throw to the plate immediately. If R3 stays, continue the rundown with the goal of one throw to the SS for the tag. The key is: the throw to second should only happen when you've confirmed R3 isn't going.","Running the runner back to first resets the situation to exactly where it started: R1, R3, 0 outs. You've gained nothing. Per RUNDOWN_MAP, always chase TOWARD the next base to create forward progress. Even if you tag the runner going back to first, you still have R3 with no outs — worse than potentially getting the out at second AND keeping R3 at third.","Multiple throws in a rundown are how errors happen, since per RUNDOWN_MAP, the standard is one throw maximum. Each additional throw adds error probability and gives R3 more time to read and break for home. Chase hard, close the gap, one throw, tag.","Throwing immediately to second gives up control. Per RUNDOWN_MAP, the fielder with the ball dictates the rundown by running at the caught runner. An immediate throw from first to second gives the runner time to stop, reverse, and potentially get back to first. You want to chase him into a closing trap, not play catch over his head."],
        rates:[80,15,20,25],concept:"Per RUNDOWN_MAP: chase toward the next base, one throw max. Per FIRST_THIRD_MAP: maintain R3 awareness and redirect home if he breaks. The 1B and catcher split the dual-responsibility.",anim:"rundown"},
      {pos:"shortstop",id:"sr7a3b",conceptTag:"rundown-mechanics",title:"SS: Close the Gap",diff:3,cat:"fielder",ageMin:12,ageMax:99,
        options:["Stand at second base and wait for the 1B to run the runner to you","Close the gap toward the runner from the second-base side — shorten the runway for a quick tag","Stay near your normal position and watch R3 at third in case he breaks","Shade toward third base to cut off R3 if he tries to advance"],
        best:1,explanations:["Per RUNDOWN_MAP, standing on the bag leaves too much runway. The rundown should end between the bases, not at the bag. If you stand at second and the runner reverses, the 1B has to chase again and make another throw — violating the one-throw principle. Close the gap so when you receive the throw, you're close enough for an immediate tag.","Per RUNDOWN_MAP, the receiving fielder closes the gap toward the incoming runner. This shortens the 'runway' so the runner has nowhere to escape. When the 1B throws, you receive it close to the runner and apply the tag immediately. The shorter the runway, the fewer throw opportunities and the faster the out. One throw, immediate tag.","Watching R3 is the catcher's primary assignment per FIRST_THIRD_MAP. Your job is to execute the rundown and get the out on the caught runner. Two fielders watching R3 means nobody is closing the gap on the runner, and the rundown stalls.","Shading toward third takes you away from the rundown entirely. Third base coverage is handled by the third baseman (if he's not involved in the rundown). Your involvement is between first and second."],
        rates:[20,80,25,15],concept:"Per RUNDOWN_MAP: close the gap toward the incoming runner from the second-base side. The shorter the runway, the fewer throws needed. One throw + immediate tag = efficient rundown.",anim:"rundown"},
      {pos:"catcher",id:"sr7a3c",conceptTag:"first-third",title:"Catcher: R3 Surveillance",diff:3,cat:"catcher",ageMin:12,ageMax:99,
        options:["Watch the runner at third exclusively — communicate to 1B if R3 breaks for home","Stay at home plate and prepare for a potential throw home from the rundown","Go to first base to cover the bag the 1B vacated","Move up the third-base line to cut off R3 before he reaches home"],
        best:0,explanations:["Per FIRST_THIRD_MAP, the catcher is the primary R3 surveillance in a first-and-third rundown. Your view of both the rundown and R3 is the best on the field. Communicate loudly: 'He's going!' if R3 breaks, or 'He's holding!' to let the 1B focus on the rundown. Your voice triggers the 1B's decision to throw to second (R3 holds) or throw home (R3 breaks). Stay at the plate in receiving position — you need to be ready for a throw home if R3 commits.","Staying at the plate is part of the job, but the active surveillance and communication is what makes you valuable. Silently waiting for a throw means the 1B has to split his attention between the rundown AND watching R3. Your voice eliminates that split.","Covering first base is a second baseman or pitcher responsibility when the 1B leaves to chase the runner. Your position at home plate is critical for the potential play on R3. Leaving home uncovered is a catastrophic defensive gap.","Moving up the third-base line takes you out of position to receive a throw at home. If R3 breaks and the throw comes home, nobody's there to catch it. Your value is at the plate, not in between bases."],
        rates:[80,50,15,20],concept:"Per FIRST_THIRD_MAP, the catcher is R3 surveillance in a first-and-third rundown. Communicate loudly: 'He's going!' or 'He's holding!' to trigger the 1B's throw decision.",anim:"rundown"},
      {pos:"secondBase",id:"sr7a3d",conceptTag:"rundown-mechanics",title:"2B: Coverage Behind the Rundown",diff:3,cat:"fielder",ageMin:12,ageMax:99,
        options:["Cover first base since the 1B left to chase the runner in the rundown","Cover second base behind the SS in case the runner slips past the tag","Position between first and second as a backup receiver in case of an overthrow","Stay near your normal position and let others handle the rundown"],
        best:0,explanations:["Per RUNDOWN_MAP, when the first baseman leaves to chase a runner, someone must cover first base. The second baseman is the natural coverage. If the rundown results in the runner being chased back toward first, someone needs to be there to receive a throw and make the tag. Additionally, if R3 scores and the batter is still at the plate, first base needs coverage for the next play.","The SS is already closing the gap from the second-base side. Two fielders at second creates redundancy and leaves first base uncovered. Per standard coverage, the SS handles the receiving role in this rundown while you cover first.","Positioning between first and second puts you in no-man's land. You're not close enough to either base to make a play. Cover first decisively — the rundown fielders handle the space between bases.","Staying at your normal position with the 1B out of position means first base is uncovered. Every fielder adjusts when a teammate leaves their position. Your rotation to first is automatic in rundown situations."],
        rates:[80,25,20,15],concept:"Per RUNDOWN_MAP, when the 1B leaves to chase a runner, the 2B covers first base. Coverage rotation is automatic — every vacated base needs a fielder.",anim:"rundown"},
      {pos:"baserunner",id:"sr7a3e",conceptTag:"first-third",title:"Runner on Third: The Read Framework",diff:3,cat:"baserunner",ageMin:12,ageMax:99,
        options:["Break for home the instant the rundown starts — the defense is distracted","Wait for the throw to go toward second base (away from home), then break with full commitment","Hold at third no matter what — the defense is watching for exactly this","Take an aggressive secondary lead but only score on an overthrow or error"],
        best:1,explanations:["Breaking immediately is the predictable play that smart defenses expect. Per FIRST_THIRD_MAP, the 1B and catcher are specifically watching for this. An immediate break gives the 1B an easy throw home with no decision conflict — you're running into the tag.","Per FIRST_THIRD_MAP, the runner at third reads the ball direction. When the ball is thrown toward second base, the fielders' momentum is carrying them AWAY from home plate. Their bodies, eyes, and throwing angles are all pointed toward second. This is your window. Break with full commitment — no hesitation, no halfway. The key: the ball must be traveling away from you (toward second) before you go. If the 1B holds the ball while looking at you, stay.","Holding unconditionally at third wastes a golden opportunity. Per FIRST_THIRD_MAP, the first-and-third rundown is one of the best scoring chances for the offense. The defense is occupied with two problems simultaneously. With zero outs, the risk of being thrown out at home is acceptable because the team still has R1 on base and at most one out.","Waiting only for errors is too passive. The throw toward second IS your trigger — it doesn't require an error. The fielder's momentum toward second makes the throw home difficult even on clean plays. Overthrows are a bonus, but the normal throw-to-second trigger is the play."],
        rates:[20,80,15,25],concept:"Per FIRST_THIRD_MAP: score from third when the ball travels toward second (away from home). The fielders' momentum carries them away from the plate — that's your window.",anim:"score"}
    ]},
  {id:"sr8a3",title:"Tag-Up at the Warning Track (All-Star)",emoji:"🏷️",color:"#ec4899",diff:3,
    situation:{inning:"Bot 5",outs:1,count:"0-0",runners:[3],score:[1,2]},
    desc:"Deep fly ball to center. Per TAGUP_SACRIFICE_FLY_MAP, the sacrifice fly has an RE24 value of +0.67 runs in this situation (R3/1 out \u2192 bases empty/2 outs). Four positions must read the same play from different angles.",
    debrief:"Per TAGUP_SACRIFICE_FLY_MAP, the sac fly from R3 with 1 out has an RE24 value: R3/1 out = 0.99 expected runs. After the sac fly scores a run: bases empty/2 outs = 0.11. The run scored minus the RE24 change = about +0.67 net value. The CF caught the ball with momentum toward home, crow-hopped for an extra 5-10 mph, and threw on a line. The runner tagged on contact, read the throw quality (strong, on-line), and the third base coach held him. The first baseman positioned as the cutoff man between the CF and home per CUTOFF_RELAY_MAP. The coach, runner, and outfielder all read the same play differently based on their role — that's what makes tag-up plays a team decision.",
    teamworkTakeaway:"Per TAGUP_SACRIFICE_FLY_MAP: the sac fly is a +0.67 RE24 net value play. The CF throws with momentum and crow-hop, the runner reads depth and throw quality, the 1B is the cutoff per CUTOFF_RELAY_MAP, and the 3B coach sees the whole play. Each role reads the same play through a different lens.",
    questions:[
      {pos:"centerField",id:"sr8a3a",conceptTag:"of-depth-arm-value",title:"CF: Momentum Transfer and Throw Quality",diff:3,cat:"fielder",ageMin:12,ageMax:99,
        options:["Catch with momentum toward home, crow-hop, and throw on a line to the plate","Catch the ball and throw home immediately without a crow-hop for maximum speed","Catch and throw to the cutoff man to let the infield decide the play","Catch and fake the throw home to freeze the runner, then throw to second to get the batter"],
        best:0,explanations:["Per TAGUP_SACRIFICE_FLY_MAP, the outfielder's throw mechanics on a sac fly attempt are: catch cleanly with body momentum toward home, crow-hop to transfer energy from legs to arm, and deliver on a low line (not a rainbow). The crow-hop adds 5-10 mph to the throw — that's the difference between beating the runner and not. A low line throw reaches the catcher on one hop at most, maintaining velocity. A rainbow throw loses speed at its apex and arrives late.","Throwing without a crow-hop uses arm only. The crow-hop transfers ground force through the legs and core into the throwing arm, adding 5-10 mph. On a 300+ foot throw, that velocity difference translates to 0.3-0.5 seconds. Given that tag-up plays are decided by fractions of a second, the crow-hop is essential, not optional.","Throwing to the cutoff man instead of home on a tag-up play adds a relay link that slows the ball down. On a tag-up from third, the throw needs to go directly home — the distance (200-280 feet from warning track to home) is within a strong outfield arm's range. The cutoff man is there as insurance if the throw is offline, not as the primary target.","Faking the throw home to freeze the runner is only effective if the runner hasn't already tagged up. On a deep fly with one out, any competent runner tags up automatically. A fake throw wastes your arm motion and momentum while the runner reads your hesitation and scores easily. The sac fly RE24 value (+0.67) makes the run attempt highly justified."],
        rates:[80,50,20,15],concept:"Per TAGUP_SACRIFICE_FLY_MAP: catch with momentum toward home, crow-hop for +5-10 mph, throw on a low line. The crow-hop converts a 0.3-0.5 second deficit into a viable throw.",anim:"throwHome"},
      {pos:"baserunner",id:"sr8a3b",conceptTag:"tag-up",title:"Runner on Third: Depth and Throw Read",diff:3,cat:"baserunner",ageMin:12,ageMax:99,
        options:["Tag up and go home on any fly ball to the outfield — the sac fly is too valuable to pass up","Tag up on the catch, take 2-3 hard steps, and read the throw: go if weak/offline, hold if strong/on-line","Only tag up on fly balls to the corners — center field is too close for a sac fly","Hold at third and only score on a dropped ball or base hit"],
        best:1,explanations:["Tagging on every fly ball without reading the throw gets you thrown out on shallow flies and strong-armed outfielders. Per TAGUP_SACRIFICE_FLY_MAP, runners score on sac flies approximately 88% of the time overall, but that drops significantly on shallow flies or throws from elite arms. The 88% rate includes the fact that smart runners DON'T go on unfavorable reads — if everyone went on every fly, the rate would be much lower.","Per TAGUP_SACRIFICE_FLY_MAP, this is the optimal tag-up framework. Touch the base on the catch (your rear foot stays on the base until the ball hits leather). Take 2-3 explosive steps toward home — you're building momentum. During those steps, read: (1) outfielder's momentum — falling backward = weak throw, (2) throw trajectory — rainbow = slow, line drive = fast, (3) throw accuracy — offline = go, on-line = hold. The read happens while you're in motion, not while standing still. The sac fly RE24 net value is +0.67 runs, making it a high-value play when the read is favorable.","Excluding center field eliminates a huge percentage of tag-up opportunities. Warning-track catches in center are deep enough to tag on against most arm strengths. The depth of the catch matters more than the position. A warning-track catch in center is 380+ feet from home — a very long throw even for elite arms.","Holding at third with one out wastes the sac fly opportunity. Per TAGUP_SACRIFICE_FLY_MAP, the sac fly has a net RE24 value of +0.67 — it's one of the most valuable plays in the baserunner's arsenal. You can't collect that value by standing on third."],
        rates:[25,80,15,10],concept:"Per TAGUP_SACRIFICE_FLY_MAP: tag up, take 2-3 explosive steps, and read the throw quality. Go on weak/offline throws, hold on strong/on-line. The sac fly net RE24 value is +0.67.",anim:"score"},
      {pos:"firstBase",id:"sr8a3c",conceptTag:"relay-double-cut",title:"1B: Cutoff Man Assignment",diff:3,cat:"fielder",ageMin:12,ageMax:99,
        options:["Position as the cutoff man between the CF and home plate, in line with the throw","Stay at first base in case the batter rounds first after the catch","Back up the catcher behind home plate in case the throw gets through","Move toward second base to cover the bag if the batter tries to advance"],
        best:0,explanations:["Per CUTOFF_RELAY_MAP, on fly balls to center field with a potential play at home, the first baseman is the cutoff man. Position approximately 60-80 feet from home plate in a direct line between the outfielder and home. Arms up for visibility. Your role: (1) let the throw go through if it's on-line and the runner is going — the catcher signals 'no cut,' (2) cut and hold if the runner retreats to third, (3) cut and throw to another base if there's a play elsewhere. The cutoff man is the relay system's decision point.","First base coverage after a caught fly ball is irrelevant. The batter is out — there's no play at first. With one out becoming two outs, the defensive priority is preventing the run from scoring, not covering an unoccupied base.","Backing up home is the pitcher's assignment per BACKUP_MAP, not the first baseman's. The 1B's value is in the cutoff position where he can redirect the throw. Two people behind the plate creates redundancy while leaving the cutoff position vacant.","Second base coverage is unnecessary on a tag-up play from third. The only play that matters is at home plate. The batter is already out (second out), and there are no other runners to advance."],
        rates:[80,10,25,15],concept:"Per CUTOFF_RELAY_MAP, the 1B is the cutoff man on CF throws home. Position in line between outfielder and home, arms up. Cut and redirect, or let it through based on the catcher's call.",anim:"throwHome"},
      {pos:"manager",id:"sr8a3d",conceptTag:"tag-up",title:"3B Coach: The Send/Hold Decision",diff:3,cat:"manager",ageMin:12,ageMax:99,
        options:["Send every runner on every deep fly — the sac fly is too valuable to pass up","Read the catch depth, outfielder's momentum and arm angle, throw trajectory, then decide send or hold","Always hold the runner — don't risk the out when you're trailing by one and the runner is already in scoring position","Pre-decide based on the outfielder's known arm strength before the pitch"],
        best:1,explanations:["Sending everyone on everything ignores the variables that determine success. Per TAGUP_SACRIFICE_FLY_MAP, the overall sac fly success rate is ~88%, but that's an average. Against elite arms from shallow warning track, it drops to 60-70%. Against average arms from deep warning track, it rises to 95%+. The coach's value is in reading the specific play, not applying blanket rules.","Per TAGUP_SACRIFICE_FLY_MAP, the third base coach has the best angle on the play. You see: (1) catch depth — warning track vs. shallow outfield, (2) outfielder's momentum — moving toward home (strong throw) vs. falling backward (weak throw), (3) arm angle — over-the-top (accurate) vs. off-balance, (4) throw trajectory — line drive (fast) vs. rainbow (slow). Process these in 0.5-1.0 seconds. The runner trusts your call. Down by one with one out, a sac fly ties the game (net RE24 +0.67). Send when the read is favorable, hold when the throw will beat the runner.","Always holding is giving up the sac fly's +0.67 RE24 net value. Down by one with one out, tying the game on a sac fly is an extremely high-value outcome. The runner is at third with one out (RE24 = 0.99) — but only if you actually attempt to score does that value convert to a run.","Pre-deciding based on arm reputation ignores situational variables. A strong-armed outfielder catching at the wall while falling backward has a much weaker throw than the same outfielder catching at medium depth with momentum. Arm strength is one factor — momentum, depth, balance, and throw trajectory all matter."],
        rates:[20,80,15,50],concept:"Per TAGUP_SACRIFICE_FLY_MAP: the 3B coach reads depth, momentum, arm angle, and trajectory in <1 second. The sac fly net RE24 value is +0.67 — send when the read is favorable, hold when the throw will win.",anim:"score"}
    ]}
]

